<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP, White House Battle Over Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican congressional leaders and the White  
House traded charges of partisanship and obstructionism over the 
budget Saturday. Each side declared that only it has the wisdom to 
save Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the harsh words, the House's four top leaders pledged in  
a letter to President Clinton to cooperate ``to resolve our 
differences'' over spending bills to pay for government operations 
in the fiscal year that started Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Clinton's chief of staff, John Podesta, told the  
Republicans they should work with the administration ``to 
strengthen Social Security for the 21st century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But most of the words in both letters were far from cordial.  
</P>
<P>
	The rhetoric flew in an atmosphere embittered by prospects of an  
election next year with control of the House in the balance. The 
GOP, which gained control in 1994 for the first time in 40 years, 
has a precarious majority of 222-211, with one Democrat-leaning 
Independent and one vacancy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans' letter was signed by Speaker Dennis Hastert of  
Illinois, Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas, Majority Whip Tom 
DeLay of Texas, and J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, the House Republican 
Conference chairman. They said the GOP's best efforts were stymied 
by Democrats out ``to advance their political agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time since 1960 we funded the operations of the  
federal government without raiding Social Security and without 
raising taxes,'' they wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we are excited about our success, we understand there is  
more work ahead. And we stand ready to work with you to resolve our 
differences,'' they wrote. ``However, we are greatly concerned 
about the efforts of congressional Democrats to obstruct our work 
in order to advance their political agenda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``As we continue our work, we urge you to reject (such) attempts  
... and renew your commitment to saving 100 percent of the Social 
Security surplus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Podesta repeated the administration's position that it was  
Clinton who, in his 1998 State of the Union Address, challenged the 
Congress to ``Save Social Security First.'' Podesta said Clinton's 
budget offering for this year would have done that through 2050. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress has not yet acted on that proposal,'' he wrote.  
</P>
<P>
	Far from rebuking House Democrats, Podesta said: ``Thanks to  
Democrats in Congress, we were able to stop a Republican tax cut 
that would have undermined Social Security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton vetoed the $792 billion, and congressional leaders were  
unable to get the two-thirds majority necessary to override the 
veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Podesta, citing the Congressional Budget Office, said the final  
GOP spending bills would spend more than $17 billion of the Social 
Security surplus. He added: 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a choice: you can continue with this pointless  
partisanship, or, as the president suggested in his meeting with 
you, work with us to strengthen Social Security for the 21st 
century.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
