<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Panel Looks To Promote Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- In addition to saving itself, the  
International Olympic Committee is out to save the world. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC panel discussing reforms to the Olympic movement Saturday  
devoted as much time to the question of Olympic truces as it did to 
finances and anti-drug controls. 
</P>
<P>
	``In areas of conflict during the Olympic Games, the IOC should  
implement the proper measures in order to symbolize or enforce the 
Olympic Truce,'' read a proposal put before the 80-member reform 
panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The word ``enforce'' met immediate objections from former U.S.  
Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, a member of the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many conservatives in America will go crazy when they see  
this,'' said Kissinger, who secured a promise that the offending 
word would be dropped. The IOC already is under fire by members of 
the U.S. Congress over the recent corruption scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	After much debate, former U.N. Secretary-General Boutros  
Boutros-Ghali came up with a revised set of recommendations that 
the IOC should contact warring parties six months before the start 
of the Olympics in a bid to convince them to observe a truce for 
the duration of the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening ceremony would then evoke IOC actions in favor of a  
truce in the hopes this might be a first step toward a durable 
peace, according to the plan to be put to IOC members in December. 
</P>
<P>
	The concept of Olympic truces is based on tradition observed  
during the games in ancient Greece and is warmly supported by IOC 
president Juan Antonio Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch claimed that representations by the IOC and the  
Japanese government one week before the start of the Nagano Winter 
Olympics in February 1998 persuaded the United States to delay 
planned attacks on Iraq for refusing to cooperate with U.N. weapons 
inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The attack never came because during the games, U.N.  
Secretary-General Kofi Annan had time to go to Baghdad and 
convinced Iraqi leaders that Security Council resolutions should be 
respected,'' Samaranch said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is the idea of an Olympic truce.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
