<HEADLINE> NAACP President's Son Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A son of NAACP President Kweisi Mfume could  
face up to seven years in prison after pleading guilty to drug 
conspiracy and weapons charges and admitting he sold cocaine for 
more than two years in the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald T. Gray, 29, entered the plea Thursday in U.S. District  
Court here to a grand jury indictment charging him with three 
counts of distributing powdered cocaine and three charges of using 
the telephone to arrange drug sales. 
</P>
