<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 11 Wisc. 35, Northwestern 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Although Wisconsin rolled to another win,  
Northwestern at least forced Ron Dayne to work for four quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne rushed for 162 yards and two touchdowns, and Jamar  
Fletcher returned an interception 93 yards for a score as No. 11 
Wisconsin struggled before beating Northwestern 35-19 Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin (7-2, 5-1 Big Ten) won its fifth straight game and  
remained directly behind unbeaten No. 2 Penn State in the 
conference race. The Badgers made two key interceptions that helped 
cover up a poor defensive performance, and the Wildcats (3-5, 1-4) 
hung in gamely before the Badgers' rushing attack wore them down. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne, who played the entire game for the first time in four  
weeks, needs 321 yards in Wisconsin's final two games against 
Purdue and Iowa to break Ricky Williams' major-college career 
rushing record. He is 124 yards from passing Tony Dorsett for 
second place on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	On a gorgeous day at Ryan Field -- which was about two-thirds  
full of Wisconsin fans -- Dayne's 5-yard touchdown run early in the 
fourth quarter put the game away. It was the 68th TD of his career, 
tying him with Indiana's Anthony Thompson for the Big Ten career 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	The Badgers' offensive line, so impressive over the last month,  
struggled against Northwestern's defense. Wisconsin freshman 
quarterback Brooks Bollinger, who improved to 5-0 as a starter, 
rushed for one touchdown and threw for another. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwestern outgained the Badgers 213-193 through the first  
three quarters and did a solid job containing Dayne and his line. 
But the Wildcats threw two disastrous interceptions and committed 
too many penalties, allowing Wisconsin to win handily, if not 
easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne had 81 rushing yards in the first quarter, including 24 on  
a touchdown run through a huge hole opened by his offensive line. 
Dayne sprinted untouched into the end zone to make the score 14-0, 
but after that run, Northwestern's defense began to find holes in 
the Badgers' massive offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwestern had its only scoring chance of the first half when  
it capitalized on a partially blocked Wisconsin punt and drove to 
the Badgers' 6 in the final minute, but Mike Echols intercepted Zak 
Kustok's pass into double coverage in the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne committed a rare fumble -- just the ninth of his entire  
career -- on the first play of the second half, and Tim Long's 
22-yard field goal cut the Badgers' lead to 14-3. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wildcats were driving again when Fletcher intercepted a  
tipped pass at his own 7, ran 50 yards up the left sideline, 
reversed field and ran for the opposite corner of the end zone. 
With five yards to go, Fletcher threw a wicked shoulder shake at 
the last Northwestern tackler and pranced into the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
	Fletcher, a sophomore, has already returned four interceptions  
for touchdowns in his career, tying the Big Ten record. He picked 
off two passes in the Badgers' win over Michigan State last week 
and has five on the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne's second touchdown made the score 28-3 with 11 minutes to  
play. Northwestern made a quick touchdown drive capped by Damien 
Anderson's 8-yard TD run with 6:51 to play, but an onsides kick 
failed and Bollinger hit Chris Chambers with a 24-yard touchdown 
pass with 4:35 left to make it 35-11. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwestern added a final touchdown, capping an 80-yard drive  
with Ian Miller's 1-yard TD reception with 43 seconds left. The 
Wildcats were successful on a two 2-point conversions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin left tackle Chris McIntosh started his 47th game for  
the Badgers, breaking the school record for starts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
