<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stranded Ship Move Abandoned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COOS BAY, Ore. (AP) -- Rough seas from the fall's first major  
storm have postponed efforts to remove the beached stern section of 
the freighter New Carissa until spring, a salvage official says. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's gonna sit for the winter,'' said Joseph Coyne, onshore  
operations manager for Donjon Marine Co. Inc. of Hillside, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews had tried for the past three weeks to beat the coming  
winter and pull the 120-foot stern section off the sand using 
towlines and two powerful tugs. Last week, the rusting hulk was 
turned toward the sea, and by Monday it had been moved some 225 
feet toward the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	But the lines had to be cut Tuesday when the storm lashed the  
coast with heavy rains and wind gusts of more than 100 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weather is what halted the towing operation, and they  
can't do anything else with it in the winter,'' said Melinda 
Merrill, a spokeswoman for Donjon Marine and another salvage 
company, Fred Devine Diving &AMP; Salvage of Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	The 639-foot ship drifted aground Feb. 4 while anchored during a  
storm waiting to enter Coos Bay to pick up a load of wood chips. 
</P>
<P>
	After it was set afire with napalm to burn off as much heavy  
fuel oil as possible, the ship broke in two. About 70,000 gallons 
of oil leaked out, soiling beaches and killing several snowy 
plovers, a threatened shore bird. 
</P>
<P>
	The larger bow section was towed out to sea and, after it broke  
loose from a tug and drifted ashore 80 miles north in Waldport, it 
was towed away again and sunk with a torpedo fired by a Navy 
submarine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
