<DOCNO> APW19991030.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 11:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bocelli Makes American Opera Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                     *AN AP ENTERTAINMENT REVIEW   	
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Blind Italian tenor Andrea Bocelli stepped from  
the confines of pop music to the grand stage of opera this weekend, 
singing the lead in Massenet's ``Werther'' at the Detroit Opera 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	His silky voice leading the way, Bocelli courted music critics  
and aficionados of fine arts in his much anticipated North American 
opera debut. 
</P>
<P>
	Clad largely in evening gowns and suits, those who came to  
listen appeared receptive, applauding the moment Bocelli took the 
stage Friday night astride a white horse, opposite mezzo-soprano 
Denyce Graves. 
</P>
<P>
	Bocelli had the romantic title role, hoping to swoon a score of  
critics who were at the opera house to judge whether the 
best-selling singer who made his name in pop could carry the day in 
live opera. 
</P>
<P>
	Reviews were mixed.  
</P>
<P>
	After initially voicing doubts about Bocelli's capacity to  
maintain his sound and amplitude, Opera Magazine's Michael H. 
Margolin said Bocelli's performance improved as it went along. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time for him working on a stage like this,''  
Margolin said. ``I think the man should be given a medal of bravery 
for just doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just seven months ago, Bocelli himself questioned aloud whether  
he could, saying at the time that he didn't feel ``credible enough 
yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have to suffer a little while longer,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I was younger, if I had shown up to audition in an opera  
house, they would have suggested I check into a lunatic asylum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bocelli has said that if opera proved a comfortable fit, he  
wouldn't mind forsaking his pop career. 
</P>
<P>
	The singer, who was blinded by a soccer injury at age 12, has  
made inroads, evident in works that last week held the top two 
spots on classical's Top 10 charts: ``Aria-The Opera Album'' and 
``Viaggio Italiano.'' Both albums have been certified gold, which 
means at least 500,000 copies of each have been sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The international chart-topper has sold millions of pop and  
classical records, was nominated in January for a Grammy for best 
new artist and has performed for President Clinton and Pope John 
Paul II. 
</P>
<P>
	His albums include opera arias, though his smooth-sounding  
ballads have some believing he's more akin to pop diva Celine Dion, 
with whom he has performed a duet, than the acclaimed Three Tenors. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Bocelli took on a full-length role, he starred as  
Rodolfo in Giacomo Puccini's ``La Boheme'' in a production on the 
Italian island of Sardinia. In ``Werther,'' he sang the title role 
in the tragic opera about a man who kills himself after the woman 
he loves marries another. The opera is based on a 1774 novel by 
Goethe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit Opera performed a new production of ``Werther,''  
directed by Mario Coraddi. The set was rented from the San Diego 
Opera Company. Christopher Schaldenbrand sang the role of Albert 
and Ying Huang was Sophie. 
</P>
<P>
	About 96 percent of the tickets have been snapped up for  
Bocelli's six planned performances here through Nov. 14. Tickets 
range from $50 to $250, dwarfing the typical price at the Detroit 
Opera House of $18 to $98. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 17:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No. 5 Florida 30, No. 10 Georgia 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Steve Spurrier did his Vince Dooley  
impression Saturday. It worked, and Spurrier earned his 100th 
victory as Florida's coach in the most fitting way possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only did the 30-14 win come against Georgia, the team he  
loves to beat most, but it came in the same manner the Bulldogs 
used to stick it to the Gators for all those years. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind a defense that shut out No. 10 Georgia (6-2, 4-2  
Southeastern Conference) in the second half and an offense more 
suited to the ground than the Fun 'N Gun, the fifth-ranked Gators 
won their ninth of the last 10 in this series and took control of 
the SEC East. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Gators (7-1, 5-1) beat Vanderbilt next Saturday and South  
Carolina the following week, they'll go back to the SEC title game 
for the first time since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, they'll celebrate a victory in one of the nation's  
most storied rivalries, best known as ``The World's Largest Outdoor 
Cocktail Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's version was a watered-down affair, a game bogged  
down by steady rain in the first half, sputtering offense in the 
second, and silly penalties and a number of stalled drives the 
whole way through. 
</P>
<P>
	It was entertaining nonetheless, with a pair of defenses being  
pushed to their limits time and again and Florida's coming out 
ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice in the second half, Georgia took over inside the Florida  
40 trailing 16-14. Both times, the Gators refused to budge. On the 
second drive, Keith Kelsey forced a fumble by Jasper Sanks at the 
Florida 10 and Bennie Alexander recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida gained the field-position advantage on the next drive,  
then struck one possession later, when Bo Carroll burst through the 
right side for a 30-yard touchdown and a 23-14 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	On Georgia's next drive, Alex Brown forced another turnover at  
the Georgia 2. Doug Johnson ran in on the next play and a game that 
had been much closer was suddenly out of hand. Brown also had an 
interception on Georgia's final drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll finished with 113 yards on 13 carries and accounted for  
most of the offense in the second half. Despite Spurrier's threats 
to the contrary, Johnson lasted the entire game. He threw for all 
of his 234 yards in the first half, however, as the game turned 
into a defensive struggle, more reminiscent of 1969 than 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gators shut down Georgia quarterback Quincy Carter, holding  
him to 6-for-23 passing for just 76 yards. He had more success 
running, especially in the first half, when he sliced through the 
Florida defense on a pair of option plays for two scores and a 
14-10 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida regained the lead on a 10-play, 72-yard march for a  
16-14 lead late in the first half. From there, the defense took 
over, as Florida allowed only 14 first downs and 231 yards in 
offense, just 53 in the second half. 
</P>
<P>
	Lost somewhere in that effort, Florida's Darrell Jackson caught  
six passes for 141 yards, his sixth straight 100-yard receiving 
game, which ties Carlos Alvarez for the school record. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 00:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NYC Salutes World Champion Yankees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It's becoming a fall tradition: The New York  
Yankees winning the World Series and being rewarded with a parade 
along Manhattan's Canyon of Heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This stuff never gets old,'' Yankee manager Joe Torre said at  
a City Hall event following the parade Friday. ``This one seemed 
even better. I think you appreciate it more each time you do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of New York Yankees fans lined the road for the team's  
third ticker tape parade in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making this a yearly tradition!'' shouted Charlie Hine,  
a UPS employee from Connecticut who took off from work for the 
second straight year to cheer his team. ``We'll be back next 
year!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police Commissioner Howard Safir generously estimated the crowd  
at 3.6 million, topping the crowds for the 1996 and 1998 parades. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days earlier, with their four-game sweep of the Atlanta  
Braves, the Yankees established themselves as the team with the 
most World Series championships in the 1990s. It was the 
franchise's 25th world title -- dwarfing the runnerup St. Louis 
Cardinals' nine titles -- leading many to call the Bronx Bombers the 
team of the century. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees owner George Steinbrenner, riding on the upper level of  
a double-decker bus, cheerfully celebrated the sweep by waving a 
broom. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran designated hitter Chili Davis puffed on a victory cigar,  
while oft-suspended Darryl Strawberry -- who later broke down in 
tears while speaking at City Hall -- videotaped the madly-cheering, 
face-painted crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	World Series MVP Mariano Rivera, the unhittable reliever, had a  
float all to himself. Yogi Berra, the Hall of Fame catcher, paraded 
in a vintage car. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-five minutes before the parade's noon start, fans were  
lined six- and seven-deep on the sidewalks along the financial 
district's narrow streets. Many revelers along the parade route, 
which runs less than a mile from the Battery to City Hall, never 
got to see the actual parade. 
</P>
<P>
	At its height, the crowd around City Hall, where each Yankees  
player was given a key to the city, stretched several blocks to the 
Brooklyn Bridge. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Grimsley and her friend JoAnna DelVecchio, both 16,  
donned their Derek Jeter jerseys and ditched school for the parade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope he notices us. I would like to marry him one day.''  
Grimsley said of the Yankee shortstop. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, he's going to marry me!'' shouted DelVecchio as they both  
started laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	They weren't the only students taking the day off. High school  
attendance was down about 17 percent from an average day, the Board 
of Education said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were six arrests during the parade. One man was accused of  
igniting small fire in the ankle-deep paper along the street. A 
woman was charged with indecent exposure for appearing topless on a 
balcony above the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Paula Young, a spokesperson for the Department of Sanitation,  
estimated that 50 tons of refuse might have been collected along 
the route, compared to 43.9 tons at last year's Yankee parade. She 
added that the exact number would not be known until the refuse was 
weighed. 
</P>
<P>
	During the City Hall ceremony, Yankee Stadium organist Eddie  
Layton played, and country musician Clint Black performed a song 
with specially written lyrics honoring the champions. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitcher David Cone, a potential free agent after this season,  
was serenaded was a chant of ``One more year!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``How about two more years?'' Cone asked.  
</P>
<P>
	The mayor's administration was less gracious toward Democratic  
state assembly members who voted to repeal New York's commuter tax 
-- a move that cost the city an estimated $210 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota said the invitations were rescinded to  
send a message: Don't vote against the city's interests. 
Assemblyman Paul Tonko, a Yankees fan from upstate, said he took 
away this message: ``He puts the rude in Rudy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Yankees fans clearly enjoyed the day, some already were  
thinking about next season. One man walking along the parade route 
held up a simple handwritten sign that read: 
</P>
<P>
	``Cheer up. Only 103 days to pitchers and catchers.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 00:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
