<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Companies Stuck in Money Schemes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Big U.S. corporations are becoming entangled  
in complex schemes in which Colombian drug cartels use legitimate 
international trade to launder an estimated $5 billion a year in 
illicit profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement authorities are warning company officials to  
watch for signs they may be receiving drug money in payment for 
legal goods they make and export. U.S. Customs Service employees 
are training companies how to detect and avoid the schemes. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly signed an  
information-sharing agreement with his Colombian counterpart 
designed to aid investigations of drug trafficking and the 
money-laundering schemes, which use a process known as the 
black-market peso exchange system. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a sophisticated variation on the basic process of money  
laundering, in which illicit profits from criminal activities are 
moved through a series of bank accounts to make them appear to be 
legitimate business proceeds. 
</P>
<P>
	The black-market peso exchange, which involves purchase of U.S.  
products -- notably home appliances, consumer electronics and 
cigarettes -- for export to Colombia, is the biggest, most efficient 
money-laundering system in the Western Hemisphere, government 
officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a perfect system,'' Kelly said in a recent interview.  
``It ostensibly looks like a legitimate business deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colombian peso brokers, who act as middlemen in the scheme, give  
Colombian importers IOUs in exchange for pesos. The pesos are used 
to buy U.S. dollars from drug cartels, providing the cartels with 
clean, usable currency. Then, the brokers use the dollars to buy 
U.S. goods and smuggle them into Colombia on behalf of the 
importers, who thereby avoid high government tariffs and taxes on 
foreign currency exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-year undercover investigation by Customs agents into a  
scheme by the Mateus group of Colombia culminated in July with 
indictments against 34 people in Alabama, Florida, Louisiana, New 
Jersey, New York and Texas; seizure of 1,160 pounds of cocaine and 
$4.5 million in cash; and freezing of 65 bank accounts around the 
United States that allegedly were used to launder drug money. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight individuals charged have pleaded guilty and are scheduled  
to go on trial Nov. 8 in federal court in Mobile, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is a prime example of major U.S. corporations getting  
entangled in the money-laundering web, Customs officials say. As 
part of the drug scheme, members of the Colombian group allegedly 
ordered money to be wired to accounts in the names of Bell 
Helicopter Textron Inc., Intel Corp., Microdata Solutions Corp. and 
MicroTel International Inc., among others. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Cox, a spokesman for Bell Helicopter Textron in Fort Worth,  
Texas, said the company did nothing wrong: ``We are as much a 
victim here as anybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Santa Clara, Calif., Intel spokesman Chuck Mulloy had no  
comment on the matter. There is no listing for Microdata Solutions 
in the Tampa, Fla., area, where authorities said the company is 
headquartered, and law enforcement officials did not have a contact 
for the company. 
</P>
<P>
	MicroTel's chief financial officer, Randolph Foote, said his  
Ontario, Calif.-based company ``has absolutely no knowledge of 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Working undercover and posing as money launderers, Customs  
agents followed the Colombians' instructions and wired drug money 
to the companies' accounts, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no evidence that any of the U.S. companies did wrong or  
should have known about the money's illicit origins. But the case 
provides an intriguing possible parallel with a huge alleged 
money-laundering scheme involving the Bank of New York, in which 
Russian companies and individuals -- including organized-crime 
figures -- are suspected of funneling billions of dollars through 
the big U.S. bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian and Russian cases are unrelated.  
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors in New York have charged a former vice  
president of the bank, her husband and a Russian business associate 
with conspiring to transmit $7 billion illegally from Russia 
through the bank. The three have denied wrongdoing. The Bank of New 
York, which has been cooperating in the investigation, was not 
charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe part of the money channeled through the  
Bank of New York could have come from thousands of small- to 
medium-sized Russian businesses that spirited funds through 
offshore companies to avoid huge taxes. The illegal practice is 
widespread in Russia, where taxes are punitive, rules often change 
and tax officials say as many as 99 percent of businesses skirt 
taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, in Colombia, the black-market peso exchange system is  
used by drug gangs to evade the country's import and foreign 
currency laws and tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Bank of New York case, several well-known corporations,  
including General Electric Co., Hewlett-Packard Co., Motorola Inc., 
Nestle SA, Volkswagen AG and DaimlerChrysler AG, received money 
wired from Bank of New York accounts that are under investigation, 
according to law enforcement officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The accounts in question were owned by a small company called  
Benex International Co. Inc. of New York, which acted as a transfer 
service for Russian importers in an apparent attempt to avoid 
Russian taxes and import duties. Benex and its Russian owner were 
named as defendants in the federal indictment. The owner, who now 
lives in London, is married to the former Bank of New York vice 
president, who also was charged. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
