<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rams and Titans Playing Like Champs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sunday's Rams-Titans game is a microcosm of the wacky 1999 NFL  
season -- a big game between two teams whose only recent notoriety 
has come from changing cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each week has been some kind of test,'' said coach Dick  
Vermeil, whose Rams (6-0) are the season's most pleasant surprise 
after going 22-42 their first four seasons in St. Louis. ``I think 
our players are looking forward to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams and Titans (5-1) have arrived at this point in markedly  
different ways, although both have had relatively easy schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis, with former Arena Leaguer Kurt Warner throwing 18  
touchdown passes, is outscoring its opponents by an average of 
nearly 26 points. The Titans have two victories by three points and 
two others by one point. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher has a decision to make at  
quarterback. Steve McNair, who missed the past five games after 
back surgery, might be ready to start. If he's healthy, he will, 
even though Neil O'Donnell is 4-1 in his place. 
</P>
<P>
	There's no question about the Rams' starter.  
</P>
<P>
	Warner, left unprotected in last spring's expansion draft, is on  
a pace to tie Dan Marino's single-season record of 48 TD passes. He 
has plenty of help, led by Marshall Faulk, who has run for 312 
yards in the past two weeks, and Isaac Bruce, who has eight TD 
catches. 
</P>
<P>
	All this leads to a lot of hoopla, although Fisher is trying to  
keep things low-key. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can overkill, you can overload, you can spend too much  
time on an opponent,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Did anyone say ``Super Bowl Preview?''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	In other games Sunday, Buffalo is at Baltimore, Carolina at  
Atlanta, Chicago at Washington, Cleveland at New Orleans, 
Jacksonville at Cincinnati, the New York Giants at Philadelphia, 
San Diego at Kansas City, New England at Arizona, Miami at Oakland, 
Dallas at Indianapolis, Minnesota at Denver, and Tampa Bay at 
Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle is at Green Bay Monday night.  
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh, the New York Jets and San Francisco are off.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
             *Seattle (4-2) at Green Bay (4-2) (Monday night)    	
</P>
<P>
	The main story is the return of Mike Holmgren to the city where  
he built a Super Bowl champion and, like Vince Lombardi, got a 
street named after him. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren views this as a test for his Seahawks against what he  
says is one of the NFL's premier teams. In truth, Green Bay's 31-3 
win over San Diego last week was its first decisive victory. Brett 
Favre had to pull out the first three with game-winning drives in 
the final minute. 

</P>
<P>
                  *Dallas (4-2) at Indianapolis (4-2)    	
</P>
<P>
	Dallas' last two road games were 13-10 losses to the Eagles and  
Giants, but their 38-20 win over Washington left them in a tie with 
the Redskins for the NFC East lead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts already have more victories than they had in each of  
the past two 3-13 seasons. Two ways to measure their progress: the 
Colts are favored, and Pat Summerall and John Madden are doing the 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Indianapolis is using history as an incentive.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you talk about Dallas, they've been a dominant team in  
this league for a number of years,'' coach Jim Mora said. 
``Whenever you play them, it's special. I think everybody feels 
this way.'' 

</P>
<P>
                   *Minnesota (3-4) at Denver (2-5)    	
</P>
<P>
	This was supposed to be last year's Super Bowl until the Vikings  
blew the NFC title game to Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings finally showed signs of offense last week, beating  
the 49ers 40-16 with Jeff George at quarterback for Randall 
Cunningham. 
</P>
<P>
	One bright light for injury-ravaged Denver is Olandis Gary, a  
late-round pick from Georgia -- just like the injured Terrell Davis 
-- who has run for 214 yards the past two weeks. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Miami (5-1) at Oakland (4-3)    	
</P>
<P>
	Damon Huard remains in for Dan Marino for the Dolphins, while  
Rich Gannon, the Raiders' quarterback, has a broken finger on his 
left hand. Gannon wants to play; coach Jon Gruden probably will 
start Bobby Hoying. 
</P>
<P>
	This game will almost surely be close. All seven Raiders games  
have been decided by a touchdown or less. The Dolphins beat Denver 
by 17 the opening week, but their other four wins are by a total of 
10. 

</P>
<P>
                  *San Diego (4-2) at Kansas City (4-2)    	
</P>
<P>
	These are two of the four plus-.500 teams in the AFC West  
(everyone but Denver). And they are two of the half-dozen or so 
teams responsible for the dearth of scoring -- both play excellent 
defense but plod on offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers have had 10 passes intercepted the past two weeks,  
seven thrown by Erik Kramer and three by Jim Harbaugh. That's 
dangerous against the Chiefs, whose plus-9 turnover differential 
leads the league. 

</P>
<P>
                   *Tampa Bay (3-3) at Detroit (4-2)    	
</P>
<P>
	Tony Dungy finally is replacing Trent Dilfer with Eric Zeier.  
``It's not a one-game thing,'' Dungy said. ``I don't like to make 
quarterback changes quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is a key game in the bunched NFC Central, where 1 1/2 games  
separate the top (Lions and Packers) from the bottom (Vikings and 
Bears). The Bucs have problems when they head north -- they've lost 
at Green Bay and Minnesota this season and last year went 1-3 on 
the road in the division. 

</P>
<P>
                  *Chicago (3-4) at Washington (4-2)    	
</P>
<P>
	Dan (The Fan) Snyder, the Redskins' owner, went ballistic after  
his team lost in Dallas, and threatened more firings. Imagine what 
might happen if they lose this. 
</P>
<P>
	Dick Jauron has the Bears playing about as well as anyone could  
ask. They're another team that plays them close -- none of their 
games has been decided by more than a touchdown. 

</P>
<P>
                 *Cleveland (0-7) at New Orleans (1-5)    	
</P>
<P>
	The Browns seem a throwback to the expansion teams of yore, like  
Tampa Bay, which lost its first 26 games. The Saints are playing 
just as poorly and Mike Ditka admits he's coaching in a befuddled 
manner. His clock management the past two weeks has been atrocious. 
</P>
<P>
	Of note: The Bucs' first-ever win, in 1977, was a 33-14 victory  
over the Saints. 

</P>
<P>
                *Jacksonville (5-1) at Cincinnati (0-6)    	
</P>
<P>
	The Jaguars had last week off and may get back their two best  
offensive players, Mark Brunell and Fred Taylor. But the sad fact 
is that they hardly need them until the playoffs. The defense is 
playing well and the schedule is full of games like this. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati is falling apart.  
</P>
<P>
	``Things that could have been taken care of maybe three or four  
years ago are now catching up with this team,'' said offensive 
tackle Willie Anderson of the Bengals, losers of 102 games this 
decade. ``You have some guys on this team that are good, 
NFL-caliber players, and you have some at certain key positions 
that maybe they're not.'' 

</P>
<P>
              *New York Giants (4-3) at Philadelphia (2-5)    	
</P>
<P>
	The Giants turned over the ball five times in their first  
meeting and still won, 16-15. That seemed to inspire the Eagles, 
who ran off their first two-game winning streak since 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	New York lost both free safeties, Percy Ellsworth and Shaun  
Williams, in its 31-3 victory over New Orleans last week. It 
probably was a good time for those injuries -- the Eagles' passing 
offense is the worst in the league. 

</P>
<P>
                  *New England (5-2) at Arizona (2-4)    	
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots' only ``blowout'' was a 12-point win over poor  
Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals are without Jake Plummer, who broke a finger  
against the Redskins. But Plummer had been having a bad year 
anyway, and Dave Brown, his backup, has 53 NFL starts, making him 
experienced, if not necessarily accomplished. 

</P>
<P>
                   *Buffalo (4-3) at Baltimore (2-4)    	
</P>
<P>
	The banged-up Bills have lost two in a row and miss wide  
receiver Eric Moulds, out with a hamstring injury for another few 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But at least they have Doug Flutie. The Ravens are going to  
their third quarterback, Tony Banks; Scott Mitchell and Stoney 
Case, have only four touchdown passes and 10 interceptions between 
them. 

</P>
<P>
                   *Carolina (2-4) at Atlanta (1-6)    	
</P>
<P>
	Dan Reeves has the Falcons still trying, but Jamal Anderson's  
absence really showed when Atlanta failed on three attempts from 
the 1-yard line at the end of Monday night's 13-9 loss in 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolina? ``We haven't quite got the mentality that it takes to  
win on a consistent basis,'' said quarterback Steve Beuerlein, who 
once was a backup on Dallas' Super Bowl teams. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
