<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mars Polar Lander Fixes Flight Path </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The Mars Polar Lander successfully  
performed a 12-second thruster firing Saturday to fine tune its 
flight path to arrive on the Red Planet's south pole on Dec. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Preliminary data showed that the adjustment, which began at  
10:28 a.m. PDT, achieved the desired change in trajectory, said 
Mary Beth Murrill, spokeswoman for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory 
in Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists and engineers had checked -- and double-checked -- the  
thruster firing process in order to avoid a repeat of the problem 
that doomed NASA's Mars Climate Orbiter. 
</P>
<P>
	Trajectory correction maneuvers are routine in solar system  
flights but the procedure for Mars Polar Lander has come under 
greater scrutiny since the loss of its companion mission in 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Martin Astronautics, which was participating in the  
Climate Orbiter mission, sent files of data in English units of 
measurement to JPL navigators who were expecting metric units. The 
undetected problem led the craft too close to Mars on Sept. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Another trajectory correction maneuver on the Polar Lander is  
scheduled for Nov. 30, three days before the lander enters the 
atmosphere and sets down on rolling plains near the Martian south 
pole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 01:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kwan Perfect At Skate America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- From her first big tests at UCLA  
to her first big test of the figure skating season, Michelle Kwan 
is one busy woman. One productive one, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Kwan, a freshman at UCLA, is no newcomer to bigtime skating  
events. Or to perfect marks. On Friday night, she swept the panel 
of nine and got a perfect 6.0 from the Russian judge in winning the 
short program at Skate America. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm out there thinking that this is cool,'' the two-time world  
champion and 1998 Olympic silver medalist said. ``It's a good 
change. This week, I'm at Skate America. Last week, I was doing 
midterms. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's given me a better perspective. I'm having more fun,  
letting it go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She let go to Beatles music for the first time in her career --  
albeit Jeff Beck's searing interpretation of ``A Day in the Life.'' 
She was as smooth as freshly cleaned ice. Kwan nailed a double axel 
to start off, hit a lovely triple lutz-double toe loop combination, 
and a triple toe. Her spins were precise and her trademark spirals 
were long and exquisite. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have that competitive feeling, even though I have  
school to juggle,'' said Kwan, who has put up with a hectic pace of 
school and practice sessions at two rinks. ``I know I can do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Carroll, coach of the three-time U.S. champion, seemed  
stunned by which judge gave Kwan the 6.0 -- her 21st in 
Olympic-eligible competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Russian, that's got to be a first,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Second heading into tonight's free skate, worth two-thirds of  
the total score, was Sarah Hughes, the 14-year-old rising star from 
Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Men's leader Alexei Yagudin of Russia wasn't quite as impressive  
as Kwan, but he also swept the judges. Yagudin, coming off an ankle 
injury, has a shaky triple axel-double toe combination and his 
spins were slow. But he did land a quadruple toe and he has a 
special presence on the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was injured and I didn't want to come here,'' he said. ``But  
then I felt better and decided I wanted to come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two-time world champion edged Americans Michael Weiss and  
Tim Goebel, even though he is using the season's first major 
international competition as a tune-up -- he will get no points here 
in the Grand Prix series because he will compete in two other 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know which of the competitions I get points. Is this  
one?'' he said, drawing laughs. ``I don't think about points. 
People expect me to skate well all the time. I try to make the 
people happy to see me skate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss stepped out of his quad, but had a strong triple  
axel-triple toe combination. 
</P>
<P>
	Weiss, who became a father for the second time last week and has  
been fighting a sore ankle and a sinus infection, was pleased with 
his opening performance of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been an interesting couple of weeks for me,'' he said.  
``It's a big step to know with things not going smoothly, I can put 
out a short program that was solid. It's a big help for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three-time world champion Elvis Stojko of Canada was just behind  
Goebel, mainly because Goebel hit his quad salchow and Stojko 
didn't attempt a quad. Stojko also put his hand down on a triple 
axel combination. 
</P>
<P>
	Goebel was more impressed that he had strong artistic marks,  
previously a weak area. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the first time ever, my artistic marks substantially  
improved in some cases. It was definitely a change I needed,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The day's biggest surprise came in pairs, with two-time world  
champions Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze fourth in the 
short program. She fell on side-by-side triple toe loops, and then 
went down again on a throw triple loop. 
</P>
<P>
	That left plenty of room for Canadians Jamie Sale and David  
Pelletier to win the short. Even though they form the No. 2 couple 
in Canada, Sale and Pelletier easily outdistanced more established 
pairs from Germany and France. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very strong competition,'' Pelletier said. ``Eight  
teams are here and six were in the top 10 at worlds. We are very 
surprised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not at all surprising -- as if there ever are any stunners in ice  
dancing -- the leaders after the compulsories and original dance 
were favorites Irina Lobacheva and Ilia Averbukh of Russia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
