<DOCNO> APW19991030.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 03:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Waves Take Bride in Calif. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PACIFIC GROVE, Calif. (AP) -- Five days after he promised to  
stand at her side through good times and bad, Eamon Stookesberry 
did the last thing he could for his wife, Jennifer. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple were taking pictures 20 feet above the pounding  
Pacific surf when 10-foot waves crashed above them and swept her 
out to sea. 
</P>
<P>
	Stookesberry dove in after his wife, and touched her hand  
briefly before the turbulent sea tore them apart about 50 yards 
from shore, a Coast Guard spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, this is really bad water here, but I'll die with  
her before I let her go,'' Stookesberry said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	As rescuers worked to reach her, ``we saw her swimming and  
staying afloat for 10 to 12 minutes,'' said Dorothy Maras-Ildiz, 
manager of the nearby Old Bath House restaurant. ``But then a huge 
set of waves came up, three or four of them, one behind the other 
and I thought, oh no, because she was getting weaker. And then, a 
few minutes later, we saw her floating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers first pulled Stookesberry, 28, from the 56-degree water  
into their boat before reaching Mrs. Stookesberry, 23. She was 
pronounced dead at a hospital. Her husband was treated for 
hypothermia. 
</P>
<P>
	The conditions that took Mrs. Stookesberry's life hit the Santa  
Cruz and Monterey areas right around high tide, spawning giant 
waves that crashed under sunny skies amid balmy temperatures that 
lured big-wave surfers to the water. 
</P>
<P>
	Several got in trouble, including 20-year-old Danny Jordan of  
San Jose, who died surfing in waters near Capitola. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard in Monterey knew of four surfers who were in  
distress at the same time. ``Between the radios and the phones, it 
was nonstop,'' Petty Officer Robert Cassidy said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a bouquet of yellow spider mums lay across the  
computer keyboard at Mrs. Stookesberry's desk in an Alamo doctors' 
office where she worked as a receptionist. 
</P>
<P>
	The spot where the Stookesberrys were taking pictures is a rocky  
outcropping called Lovers Point. Ocean spray flew over the top of 
the 40- and 50-foot Monterey cypress trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's breathtaking,'' Maras-Ildiz said, ``but nothing you  
should be standing near. Landlubbers don't understand the force. 
Rule one is you never turn your back on the ocean.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
