<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Atlanta Can Sue Gun Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The city can go ahead with its lawsuit against  
gun makers, a judge ruled, forcing the industry to open its files 
for the first time to one of the local governments suing it for the 
effects of gun-related violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Fulton County Judge Gino Brogdon's decision Wednesday came  
almost three weeks after an Ohio judge threw out a similar lawsuit 
by Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta's suit, like those of 26 other cities or counties that  
have sued the industry, came after successful suits against the 
tobacco industry by states. In those cases, the industry had to 
open secret files, revealing damaging information about decisions 
on product safety. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's the effect on the gun industry? Fear,'' said Mark  
Kadish, a Georgia State University law professor. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge allowed Atlanta to pursue its claims that guns are  
defectively designed and fail to incorporate safety devices. The 
judge said the city must prove that the industry was negligent, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	Five days after Atlanta's suit was filed in February, the  
General Assembly passed a law banning such suits by Georgia cities 
and towns. The city argued that a phrase allowing the law to take 
effect retroactively was never printed in the final copy of the 
state code. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith &AMP; Wesson argued that the law should nullify the suit, but  
Brogdon did not address that claim. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a mixed result,'' said Anne Kimball, a Smith &AMP; Wesson  
attorney. ``We continue to believe that Brogdon will dismiss the 
entire suit.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
