<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College Football Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Florida passed its biggest hurdle on the road to the SEC  
championship game -- by running the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Bo Carroll ran 30 yards for a second-half touchdown and the  
Gators held Quincy Carter to 73 yards passing as No. 5 Florida beat 
No. 10 Georgia 30-14 on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The win, coach Steve Spurrier's 100th at Florida, put the Gators  
(7-1, 5-1 Southeastern Conference) in control of the league's East 
Division. Wins over Vanderbilt and South Carolina are all the 
Gators need to reach the league's title game for the first time in 
three years. 
</P>
<P>
	At Jacksonville, Fla., Spurrier's Gators won against the team he  
loves to beat most. The defense shut out Georgia (6-2, 4-2) in the 
second half and the offense ground out yardage over the final 30 
minutes. Get this -- Florida had zero net yards passing in the 
second half. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can get that feeling where we need to put it on the  
ground,'' Spurrier said. ``When our defense is playing like they're 
playing, I can just say, `Hang onto the ball, fellows, and 
hopefully we'll break one here and there.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The game was played in a steady rain, with silly penalties and a  
number of stalled drives making if frustrating for all involved. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Gators ahead 16-14, Carroll's TD run put Florida in  
control. 
</P>
<P>
	On Georgia's next drive, Alex Brown forced a turnover at the  
Georgia 2. Doug Johnson, who threw for his 234 yards in the first 
half, ran in on the next play and a game that had been close was 
suddenly out of hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll finished with 113 yards on 13 carries.  
</P>
<P>
	In other Top 25 games, it was No. 2 Penn State 27, Illinois 7;  
No. 4 Tennessee 30, South Carolina 7; No. 6 Kansas State 48, Baylor 
7; No. 7 Georgia Tech 48, North Carolina State 21; No. 11 Wisconsin 
35, Northwestern 19; and No. 12 Texas 44, Iowa State 41. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, it was No. 13 Marshall 41, Northern Illinois 9; No. 14  
Alabama 35, No. 20 Southern Mississippi 14; No. 15 Michigan 34, 
Indiana 31; Air Force at No. 16 BYU 27, Air Force 20; No. 17 East 
Carolina 19, Houston 3; No. 18 Purdue 33, Minnesota 28; No. 21 Ohio 
State 41, Iowa 11; No. 22 Texas A&AMP;M 21, Oklahoma State 3; No. 23 
Miami 28, West Virginia 20; and Colorado 38, No. 24 Oklahoma 24. 
</P>
<P>
	In night games, it was No. 1 Florida State at Virginia; No. 3  
Virginia Tech at Pittsburgh; co-No. 8 Nebraska at Kansas; and No. 
25 Mississippi at LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-No. 8 Mississippi State and No. 19 Michigan State did not 	
play on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
                    *No. 2 Penn State 27, Illinois 7 	
</P>
<P>
	At Champaign, Ill., Rashard Casey, replacing an ineffective  
Kevin Thompson, threw for one TD and ran for another as the Nittany 
Lions (9-0, 5-0 Big Ten) won their 11th straight game. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson threw three interceptions, and coach Joe Paterno put  
Casey in late in the third quarter with the Lions ahead 10-7. Penn 
State's defense was led by end Courtney Brown, who had four sacks 
against Kurt Kittner. 
</P>
<P>
	The Illini, who upset Michigan last week, fell to 4-4, 1-4.  
</P>
<P>
                  *No. 4 Tennessee 30, South Carolina 7    	
</P>
<P>
	At Knoxville, Tenn., Jamal Lewis ran 70 yards for a TD and  
finished with 146 yards as the Vols (6-1, 4-1 SEC) handed the 
Gamecocks (0-9, 0-7) their 19th consecutive loss -- the nation's 
longest major-college losing streak. 
</P>
<P>
                    *No. 6 Kansas State 48, Baylor 7    	
</P>
<P>
	At Manhattan, Kan., David Allen ran for two TDs and caught a  
scoring pass and the Wildcats (8-0, 5-0 Big 12) held the Bears 
(1-7, 05-) to seven first downs and 119 yards. 
</P>
<P>
              *No. 7 Georgia Tech 48, North Carolina State 21    	
</P>
<P>
	At Atlanta, Joe Hamilton threw for 212 yards and three TDs and  
ran for 83 yards as the Yellow Jackets (6-1, 4-1 ACC) won their 
fifth straight game. 
</P>
<P>
                 *No. 11 Wisconsin 35, Northwestern 19    	
</P>
<P>
	At Evanston, Ill., Ron Dayne ran for 162 yards and two TDs, and  
Jamar Fletcher had a 93-yard interception return for a score to 
lead the Badgers (7-2, 5-1 Big Ten) over the Wildcats (3-5, 1-4). 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne needs 321 yards in Wisconsin's final two games against  
Purdue and Iowa to break Ricky Williams' major-college career 
rushing record. 
</P>
<P>
                     *No. 12 Texas 44, Iowa State 41    	
</P>
<P>
	At Ames, Iowa, Kris Stockton's third field goal of the game, an  
18-yarder as time expired, lifted the Longhorns (7-2, 4-1 Big 12). 
</P>
<P>
	Major Applewhite threw for 345 yards and two TDs to save Texas,  
coming off its upset of No. 8 Nebraska. The Cyclones (4-4, 1-4) are 
looking for their first winning season since 1989. 
</P>
<P>
                *No. 13 Marshall 41, Northern Illinois 9    	
</P>
<P>
	At Huntington, W.Va., the Thundering Herd (8-0, 5-0 MAC)  
extended the nation's longest major-college winning streak to 12 
games as Chad Pennington threw for 288 yards and four TD passes 
against the Huskies (4-5, 4-2). 
</P>
<P>
            *No. 14 Alabama 35, No. 20 Southern Mississippi 14    	
</P>
<P>
	At Tuscaloosa, Ala., playing without injured stars Shaun  
Alexander and Andrew Zow, the Crimson Tide (6-2) rolled as Shaun 
Bohanon had two TD runs, Reggie Myles returned an interception for 
a score and Freddie Milons had a 65-yard punt return for a TD. 
</P>
<P>
                    *No. 15 Michigan 34, Indiana 31    	
</P>
<P>
	At Bloomington, Ind., the Wolverines (6-2, 3-2 Big Ten) needed  
Hayden Epstein's 20-yard field goal with 18 seconds left to hold 
off the Hoosiers (4-5, 3-3). 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony Thomas ran for 197 yards and three TDs for Michigan.  
Antwaan Randle El threw for 290 yards and four TDs for Indiana, 
with a final ``Hail Mary'' pass falling incomplete in the end zone 
on the game's final play. 
</P>
<P>
                      *No. 16 BYU 27, Air Force 20    	
</P>
<P>
	At Provo, Utah, BYU coach LaVell Edwards notched career win No.  
250 as Kevin Feterik threw for 336 yards and two TDs to pace the 
Cougars (7-1, 4-0 Mountain West). Air Force fell to 4-3, 1-3. 
</P>
<P>
                   *No. 17 East Carolina 19, Houston 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Houston, Anthony Adams returned a fourth-quarter interception  
55 yards for a TD as the Pirates (7-1, 3-1 C-USA) held on against 
the Cougars (4-4, 2-2) in the wind and rain. 
</P>
<P>
                    *No. 18 Purdue 33, Minnesota 28    	
</P>
<P>
	At Minneapolis, Drew Brees threw for 283 yards and two TDs and  
the Boilermakers (6-3, 3-3 Big Ten) held on against the Golden 
Gophers (5-3, 2-3). 
</P>
<P>
                     *No. 21 Ohio State 41, Iowa 11    	
</P>
<P>
	At Columbus, Ohio, Ken-Yon Rambo caught seven passes for 179  
yards, scored one TD and set up two others to pace the Buckeyes 
(6-3, 3-2 Big Ten). 
</P>
<P>
                  *No. 22 Texas A&AMP;M 21, Oklahoma State 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At College Station, Texas, Randy McCown's separated left  
shoulder didn't affect his right arm as he threw two TD passes to 
Matt Bumgardner to lead the Aggies (6-2, 3-2 Big 12) to the 600th 
win in school history. 
</P>
<P>
                   *No. 23 Miami 28, West Virginia 20    	
</P>
<P>
	At Miami, Kenny Kelly threw for 268 yards and two second-half  
TDs as the Hurricanes (4-3, 2-0 Big East) posted a second straight 
come-from-behind win. 
</P>
<P>
	Against WVU (3-5, 2-2), Miami trailed 13-0 at halftime. Last  
week, the 'Canes trailed Boston College by 28 points late in the 
third quarter before winning 31-28. 
</P>
<P>
                    *Colorado 38, No. 24 Oklahoma 24    	
</P>
<P>
	At Boulder, Colo., Mike Moschetti threw for 382 yards and four  
TDs and ran for another score as the Buffaloes (5-3, 4-1 Big 12) 
held off the Sooners (4-3, 2-2). 
</P>
<P>
	The Buffs intercepted Josh Heupel (328 yards, two TD passes)  
four times and sacked him three times. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
