<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Clarke: Keep Status Quo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Leave it to the Philadelphia Flyers to find  
themselves battling turmoil at the same time they're battling for 
first place. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers steadied themselves after an 0-5-1 start that put  
some early tarnish on their Stanley Cup hopes. A four-game winning 
streak, including three shutouts, sent them back to the top of the 
standings. Things should be fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Far from it.  
</P>
<P>
	Eric Lindros is out with a persistent, mysterious illness. Coach  
Roger Neilson survived rumors about his job, but can't shake a 
virus he's had for a month. General manager Bob Clarke looks ready 
to pounce as he stands ominously in the executive box during games. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite body language to the contrary, Clarke said Friday he's  
not going to panic -- and that means forget about trading No. 88. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trading Lindros,'' Clarke said in his New Jersey  
office, one day after the Flyers, playing without Lindros, blew a 
4-0 lead in the third period before coming back to beat Colorado 
5-4 in overtime. ``We're not trading anybody. Teams ask about a lot 
of players, but it doesn't mean you're trading them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also doesn't mean that players are immune to the rumblings,  
especially Lindros. He and his father, Carl Lindros, who is also 
his agent, make no secret of their belief that the Flyers have 
entertained trade offers for one of the most dynamic players in the 
game. Before the season, Lindros lamented having been ``shopped 
around the league'' in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Lindros and longtime linemate John LeClair are signed  
only through this season, there is no indication Clarke has 
anything in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers have more pressing concerns.  
</P>
<P>
	With forwards Rod Brind'Amour and Keith Jones sidelined with  
injuries, the Flyers started 0-5-1, the worst start in their 
32-year history. They promptly won four straight, quieting the 
alarm, but glaring weaknesses resurfaced the last two games. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros, trying to play despite his illness, had one of the  
worst games of his career Tuesday night in a 5-2 loss to Vancouver 
in which the Canucks overwhelmed Philadelphia with speed. Lindros 
and LeClair were on the ice for four Vancouver goals, and each made 
a glaring turnover that led to a score. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros has four goals in 11 games and is minus-5. LeClair  
played better Thursday night, but has four goals in 12 games and is 
minus-7. 
</P>
<P>
	With Lindros home in bed Thursday night, the Flyers blew a 4-0  
lead against the Avalanche by allowing four goals on eight shots in 
8:09. Valeri Zelepukin saved them with a goal that was supposed to 
be a pass with 8.2 seconds left in OT. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got good people in this locker room who stick  
together,'' said Mark Recchi, the Flyers' best player so far with a 
team-high five goals and 18 points. ``That's why we got through 
that 0-5-1. The concern was very minimal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke was a conspicuous presence throughout the game, standing  
and pacing around his box high above the ice. He said nothing 
should be gleaned from that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sit lots of times,'' Clarke said. ``It's just however I feel  
that night, I guess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindros, whose season was cut short last year by a scary,  
draining bout with a collapsed lung, has been sick for more than a 
week. Doctors are calling it a virus, and Clarke shot down 
speculation that Lindros was anemic. He's questionable for 
Saturday's home game against New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctors tell us that he is not anemic,'' Clarke said. ``He  
has a virus and is very run down, which is what a virus does to 
anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson, who has been sick for a month, is considering Clarke's  
offer to take a couple of days off during the team's upcoming road 
trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke suggested that Neilson, whose girlfriend lives in Dallas,  
should fly there Sunday and rest before rejoining the team 
Wednesday in Anaheim. Assistants Wayne Cashman and Craig Ramsay, 
both with head coaching experience, would run practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Neilson is wary, and rightfully so. Only two weeks ago he was  
being bombarded with questions about his job security. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always a little skeptical of being sent away, so I  
probably won't go,'' the coach said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarke made only a minor change Friday. Rookie defenseman Mark  
Eaton will be sent to the minors and defenseman Andy Delmore will 
join the team for the four-game road trip that begins next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides standing, pacing and hoping, that's all from upstairs --  
for now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't replace Lindros. We can't replace Brind'Armour,''  
Clarke said. ``You hope other people step up. That's all you can 
do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
