<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Last Indonesian Ship Leaves E.Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Under cover of darkness, the last  
Indonesian troop ship sailed out of Dili's nearly deserted harbor 
today, ending a bloody 24-year military engagement in East Timor. 
In an extraordinary farewell gesture, East Timor's rebel leader 
clasped hands with senior Indonesian military officers today as 
Indonesian forces spent their final hours in the territory. 
Peacekeeping troops sealed off the docks and kept a wary eye on a 
crowd of East Timorese who have been jeering and taunting the 
departing troops in recent days. 

</P>
<P>
	Taliban: Bin Laden Wants To Leave  
</P>
<P>
	PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) -- Osama bin Laden, wanted by the United  
States for the bombing of two American embassies last year, has 
asked for permission to leave Afghanistan, the ruling Taliban 
religious army said today. Bin Laden's departure could lift the 
threat of U.N. sanctions on Afghanistan, where he has been living 
for years. A Clinton administration official said the U.S. 
government had seen the report of bin Laden's request, but that it 
``falls far short'' of the U.N. resolution that the militia deliver 
him for trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing Delay Dismays Safety Panel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal safety investigators say they are  
dismayed that Boeing would study fuel tank problems on its jumbo 
jets but then fail for years to disclose their findings. The 
Washington Post, in today's editions, quotes National Safety 
Transportation Board officials as saying the Boeing report could 
have helped them focus on the problem -- fuel tank overheating -- 
that was an apparent factor in the explosion of TWA Flight 800 over 
Long Island Sound in 1996. According to the Post, Boeing produced 
the report in 1980 but did not give it to the NTSB until this June. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Announces Toxic Report Rules  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Companies that release even the smallest  
amounts of highly toxic chemicals into the air, water or land will 
be required to report the incident to the public, President Clinton 
said today. Current federal regulations require disclosure only by 
companies that release of large amounts of extremely toxic 
chemicals, like mercury and PCBs. The new rules, Clinton said in 
his weekly radio address, will help communities force polluting 
companies to act more responsibly. 

</P>
<P>
	S. Korea Shopping Fire Kills 54  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In the worst fire in 25 years, a blaze  
raged through a four-story building crowded with young weekend 
shoppers and diners today in northwestern South Korea, killing at 
least 54 people, many of them teen-agers, police said. Seventy 
people were injured, some of them seriously. Police reduced the 
death toll from 57, but said it may rise again because some of the 
injured people were in critical condition. The fire broke out 
around in Inchon, South Korea's third largest city, 30 miles west 
of Seoul. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Jets, Army Pound Chechnya  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Chechen authorities struggled today to  
find new ways to get refugees out of Chechnya as Russian jets and 
artillery continued to shower bombs and shells on the battered 
republic. Despite international calls for an end to the war, 
Russian forces kept up their bombardment of the capital Grozny, 
concentrating their fire on suspected guerrilla positions in the 
northern and southern outskirts. Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja 
Halonen, who led a European Union delegation to refugee camps 
today, urged Russia to open its borders and allow people to flee 
the fighting. 

</P>
<P>
	2 Churches Settle Salvation Debate  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Ending an almost 500-year debate that started when  
Martin Luther nailed his 95 theses to a church door, the Lutheran 
and Roman Catholic churches plan to sign a joint declaration 
tomorrow putting aside their differences over the way humanity 
achieves salvation. The dispute centers on the question of how to 
get to heaven. Catholics believe that people's actions can make a 
difference, while Lutherans believe salvation is based on faith 
alone. At the heart of the agreement is a statement that faith is 
essential in salvation. 

</P>
<P>
	Chiefs' Rison Arrested for Fighting  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Kansas City Chiefs wide receiver Andre  
Rison was one of six people arrested today for fighting outside a 
Kansas City nightspot, police said. Officers were called at about 2 
a.m. to a disturbance outside the Have A Nice Day Cafe in the 
city's Westport entertainment district, police spokesman Floyd 
Mitchell said. Rison, 32, signed with the Chiefs as a free agent in 
1997, after being released by the Green Bay Packers. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
