<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Paper Cites McCain for Temper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The largest newspaper in John McCain's home state  
is questioning whether the Republican senator has the temperament 
to be president. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona Republic, in an editorial running in Sunday  
editions, criticizes McCain for a ``volcanic'' temper it says he 
has unleashed on other politicians, reporters and even the public. 
</P>
<P>
	``If McCain is truly a serious contender for the presidency, it  
is time the rest of the nation learned about the John McCain we 
know in Arizona,'' the newspaper says in the editorial, a copy of 
which was provided to The Associated Press on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is also reason to seriously question whether he has  
temperament, and the political approach and skills, we want in the 
next president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pam Johnson, The Republic's senior vice president/news and  
executive editor, said Saturday the newspaper decided to run the 
editorial partly out of frustration that the American electorate is 
not getting the complete McCain story from the national media. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is very much to be admired and applauded about John  
McCain,'' Johnson said in a telephone interview with the AP. ``But 
there is a less full-bodied portrayal at this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saying McCain's temper is a legitimate campaign issue, The  
Republic notes in its editorial that he has unleashed his temper on 
several top Arizona officials -- including Gov. Jane Hull, former 
Gov. Rose Mofford and former Phoenix Mayor Paul Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	It also cites heated disagreements with fellow senators and says  
McCain has called some reporters who asked tough questions 
``liars'' and ``idiots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain spokesman Dan Schnur on Saturday did not deny that his  
boss gets angry, adding that questions about his temperament are 
fair game. But Schnur portrays McCain's anger as passion-driven, 
rather than some major character flaw. 
</P>
<P>
	``Voters ought to decide for themselves if they want a candidate  
who gets angry when they seen an injustice, or would they rather 
have someone who rolls over and hides,'' Schnur says. 
</P>
<P>
	The editorial was prompted by a recent New York Times article in  
which Mrs. Hull spoke of McCain's temper, pretending to a hold a 
telephone receiver inches from her ear for effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hull, who has endorsed Texas Gov. George W. Bush, said her  
relations with McCain were ``not particularly warm'' and that his 
temper is ``something that John has to keep control of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain blamed the Bush campaign for helping plant the story and  
said the hothead portrayal was inaccurate. ``But do I insult 
anybody or fly off the handle or anything like that? No, I don't,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republic calls McCain's reaction to Mrs. Hull's comments  
``hogwash'' and says McCain ``is running dangerously close to 
sanctimony in his bid for the presidency, depicting himself as the 
last honorable politician in America.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
