<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 13-Year-Old Said Incapable of Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) -- A murder case against one of the youngest  
defendant's in U.S. history -- a boy accused at age 11 of shooting a 
man outside a convenience store -- is as flawed as the ``piece of 
junk'' rifle that fired the fatal shot, his attorney told jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	In opening statements Friday, attorney Geoffrey Fieger said  
Nathaniel Abraham had no intent to kill anyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be zero evidence that he had any motive to kill  
Ronnie Greene,'' Fieger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene was killed outside a Pontiac party store on Oct. 29,  
1997. Prosecutors say Nathaniel knew exactly what he was doing. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Lisa Halushka said Nathaniel even told his girlfriend  
prior to the killing that ``I'm gonna shoot somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A clearer intent was never spoken,'' the prosecutor said.  
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel, now 13, is being tried as an adult on first-degree  
murder charges. If convicted, he could get life in prison without 
parole, be held in a juvenile center until he turns 18, or receive 
a blended sentence in which he would be held until age 21 and then 
re-examined. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel also is on trial on charges of firing at neighbor  
Michael Hudack hours before Greene was shot once in the head 
outside the store. 
</P>
<P>
	Fieger said Greene was killed by a bullet that bounced off a  
tree, adding that the rifle was defective and even a marksman 
aiming at Greene would have missed him with that gun. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nathaniel had a .22-caliber rifle ... it had no stock, it is a  
piece of junk,'' Fieger said. ``It couldn't shoot straight if it 
had wanted to. This is a broken weapon. It can't be aimed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police have said Nathaniel was standing about 100 yards away  
when the shot was fired. On Friday, prosecutors said tests now show 
the shot was fired from about 66 yards away. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel's lawyers also have maintained that the boy, a slow  
learner, could not have understood his rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Hudack and Oakland County's medical examiner testified later  
Friday before proceedings were recessed until Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hudack said he was home when he heard a noise resembling a  
firecracker. When he went outside, he said, something whizzed past 
his face. He said he looked to his left and spotted Nathaniel and 
another boy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nate was holding something in his hand. It appeared to be a  
gun,'' Hudack testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Under defense questioning, Hudack acknowledged he couldn't say  
with certainty who fired at him and that ``I don't know that 
(Nathaniel) was trying to shoot me or if he was shooting at the 
garage.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
