<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 11:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Outgoing Head: UN Panel Rebounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- UNESCO, a troubled U.N. organization, has  
ceased being an ivory tower for intellectuals and is helping the 
world cope with the pressures of globalization, its retiring 
director general said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain's Federico Mayor, a biochemist who has headed the U.N.  
Educational Scientific and Cultural Organization for the past 12 
years, also said the 187-nation institution now is recognized a 
leading proponent of freedom of expression. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor said in an interview he would advise his probable  
successor, Japan's Koichiro Matsuura, that the best way to get the 
United States to rejoin UNESCO is to focus more sharply on issues 
such as illiteracy and education spending by developing countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Matsuura, Japan's ambassador to France, is expected to be  
endorsed Nov. 15 by the organization's governing board, which is 
based in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and Britain left UNESCO in 1984 and 1985,  
charging the organization was corrupt, mismanaged and opposed to 
Western free press ideals. Britain returned last year but President 
Clinton has said budget constraints prevent the United States from 
rejoining. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department officials say Mayor has done a good job getting  
UNESCO back to the democratic principles on which it was founded 
after World War II -- promoting human rights and the free flow of 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics say UNESCO remains hobbled by top-heavy and  
inefficient management. They also contend Mayor spent too much of 
the $544 million biannual budget on special advisers and 
consultants. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the Associated Press by telephone from New  
York, the 65-year-old Mayor reviewed his accomplishments and 
answered criticism of his leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``UNESCO has ceased being an ivory tower and is now  
reinvigorated on the spot in the field listening to the wishes of 
officials and ordinary people and trying to counterbalance the 
technological, financial and economic imperatives that govern 
globalization,'' Mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the organization, which in the early 1980s debated a  
Soviet- approved attempt to establish a ``new world information 
order,'' now ``is recognized throughout the world as the 
institution at the forefront of freedom expression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald Koven, the European representative of the World Press  
Freedom Committee, said Mayor does not get enough credit for this 
accomplishment and has made UNESCO respectable again. 
</P>
<P>
	``He turned the organization around on press freedom,'' Koven  
said, ``and took a courageous stand against China when it 
threatened to boycott the organization after UNESCO gave a press 
freedom award to Gao Yu, a jailed Chinese journalist'' who was 
released earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor said unlike other U.N. agencies that deal with a single  
issue such as health or agriculture, UNESCO was like a university, 
managing programs that ranged from education and cultural heritage 
to preserving the world's oceans. 
</P>
<P>
	He said even though the United States was not a member, UNESCO  
had a wide range of contacts with American schools, universities 
and scientific organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best way to get the United States to come back is to keep  
accomplishing our mission in the best way we can without looking 
for pats on the back,'' Mayor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Answering critics of his management, he said independent audits  
by Congress' investigative arm, the General Accounting Office, and 
the Canadian government largely have been favorable. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been disagreements on staff policies but this  
happens at other international organizations as well,'' ' Mayor 
said. ``I have reduced staff by 1,100 posts, a third, since I took 
over but I need to use consultants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said after leaving UNESCO he would establish a private  
foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Harry Dunphy covered the press freedom debate at  
UNESCO in the 1980s and Mayor's election in 1987. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
