<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 16:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FONTANA, Calif. (AP) -- Greg Moore, who finished second in last  
year's Marlboro 500 at California Speedway, may miss Sunday's race 
after being injured in an off-track incident Saturday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Canadian driver was leaving the Player's  
Forsythe Racing motor home on a scooter when he was struck by a 
car. The driver said she had been blinded by the morning sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore sustained a minor fracture of the forefinger of his right  
hand as well as lacerations on the same hand and a bruised right 
hip. 
</P>
<P>
	He was held out of the scheduled practice and qualifying on  
Saturday, but was later given the opportunity by CART to go onto 
the two-mile oval by himself to see how it felt to drive with the 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	After six laps, three of them above 219 mph, Moore said he  
planned to drive in Sunday's race. Moore will start last in the 
27-car field. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAYING GOODBYE: Sunday will apparently be the final CART race  
for longtime star Al Unser Jr., who is parting company with 
Marlboro Team Penske and is expected to switch to the rival Indy 
Racing League in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Unser, who drove his first CART race in 1982, is second only to  
fellow second-generation driver Michael Andretti in victories with 
31 and is a two-time series champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have always enjoyed racing with Al, so it will be weird to  
not have him on the same track,'' Andretti said. ``I think Al 
really helped build our series and he will definitely be missed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unser, who has gone 69 races since his last victory, will start  
10th in Sunday's race, his 273rd CART race. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	LONG TERM: CART and California Speedway have signed a five-year  
contract extension with the intent of having the season-ending race 
at the Fontana track each season through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Craig, president and CEO of CART, said the sanctioning  
body has now come to agreement on contract extensions of three to 
five years with six tracks, including California, Mid-Ohio, 
Cleveland, Long Beach, Road America and Surfers Paradise, 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	MARIO'S AWARD: Longtime open-wheel racing star Mario Andretti,  
who retired from CART after the 1995 season, has been honored by 
CART with a new award in his name. 
</P>
<P>
	The inaugural CART All-Star Team will be announced in February,  
with the driver amassing the most votes presented with the new 
Mario Andretti Trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows that racing was my work, but also the joy of my  
life,'' said Andretti. ``It is the ultimate compliment to me that 
CART looks back at thos years and finds them so meaningful and 
worthy of recording. I am genuinely appreciative of everyone who 
continues to acknowledge my part in racing history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trophy itself was created by noted Western artist Elie  
Hazak, who specializes in bronze sculpture. It is a 38-inch tall, 
95-pound blend of bronze, marble and walnut that represents 
Andretti's years in racing with a globe, an olive tree and replicas 
of the various types of cars Andretti has driven. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SPARK PLUGS: Series leader Dario Franchitti has gone from a  
28-point deficit to a nine-point lead over rookie Juan Montoya in 
the past two races. ... Sunday will be Wally Dallenbach's last race 
as CART's chief stewart. The former Champ Car driver will stay on 
next season as a consultant and then retire. ... Firestone, which 
will become the exclusive tire supplier for CART next season with 
the announced pullout by Goodyear, has won all nine 500-mile race 
poles since it returned to the series in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
