<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Relies on Capitol Hill Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When Republican presidential front-runner  
George W. Bush roiled GOP House members this fall by criticizing 
their budget plans, Rep. Roy Blunt stepped forward to calm the 
waters. 
</P>
<P>
	At a private meeting of the rank and file, the Missouri  
Republican stressed that such public faultfinding is rare, and 
occasional disagreements are inevitable, according to one lawmaker 
who attended. ``He said it wasn't meant as a slight against 
anyone,'' this lawmaker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Blunt made his defense in his capacity as the Bush campaign  
point man in the House. He is half of a team -- Sen. Paul Coverdell 
of Georgia is his partner -- that is responsible for smoothing the 
way for the Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're friends of mine,'' Bush said in a recent interview.  
</P>
<P>
	Coverdell, 60, is a former state party chairman now in his  
second Senate term, a member of the GOP leadership. He has 
long-standing ties to the Bush family and was Peace Corps director 
in the administration of Bush's father. 
</P>
<P>
	Blunt, 49, has risen rapidly in only his second term in the  
House. He was tapped this year to serve as the GOP's chief deputy 
whip after his predecessor in that post, Rep. Dennis Hastert, was 
elevated suddenly to speaker. GOP officials say Hastert had been in 
line to be the Bush campaign's point man in the House, and Blunt 
inherited that portfolio when he moved into the whip's 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Given Bush's status, he and his campaign organization are in  
touch regularly with Republicans in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials say that when they were together in Florida recently,  
Bush thanked House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas for his 
restrained response to the budget controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert dispatched top aides to Austin this year to meet with  
campaign aides. Also, Bush's political director, Maria Cino, once 
was a top aide to former Rep. Bill Paxon, R-N.Y., who remains close 
to Hastert and the powerful GOP Whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Blunt and Coverdell say there has been no attempt to  
coordinate legislative initiatives with the Bush campaign, although 
communication back and forth is plentiful. 
</P>
<P>
	``We obviously work at being a source of information,'' says  
Coverdell. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial task for Blunt and Coverdell was to line up support  
for the Texas governor. Thus far, about 160 House members and 29 
senators have enlisted publicly -- there are others as yet 
unannounced -- backing that dwarfs any other GOP presidential 
contender's. 
</P>
<P>
	``The endorsement part of this hasn't been the hardest job I've  
ever taken on,'' Blunt says with evident understatement. About 80 
Republicans, he said, ``had gone on record before there was a 
record to go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coverdell notes that at a similar stage in the 1988 campaign,  
Bush's father had only a single Senate endorsement even though he 
was a sitting vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Other tasks are less public.  
</P>
<P>
	When the governor was on the verge of announcing his views on  
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, for example, GOP officials say 
Coverdell quietly made sure the campaign knew that 20 of 29 of his 
supporters in the Senate opposed the pact. Bush came out against 
the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials also say an effort is in the works to encourage Senate  
supporters of Bush to activate their political networks on the 
governor's behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, Coverdell has not had to handle the type of blowup  
that confronted Blunt this fall when Bush parted company with a GOP 
plan that would change a tax program designed to benefit the 
working poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think they ought to balance their budget on the backs  
of the poor,'' Bush said at the time. The comment angered many 
House Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to coming to Bush's defense, Blunt arranged for  
Republicans to meet a few weeks later to talk with senior campaign 
strategist Karl Rove. 
</P>
<P>
	Rove, too, sought to reassure lawmakers about Bush's intentions,  
Blunt said. He added that at least one other lawmaker observed that 
while Bush's comments were a rarity for him, other GOP hopefuls, 
Gary Bauer and Steve Forbes among them, routinely criticize the 
Republican majority in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	A more typical task for Blunt was triggered by Elizabeth Dole's  
decision to drop her own presidential campaign. He quickly was on 
the phone to half a dozen lawmakers who had endorsed her. In a few 
hours, all had swung behind the Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, when Bush was in Washington earlier this fall, Blunt  
arranged for a small group of uncommitted House members to sit with 
him. The session took place in a hotel suite fit for a 
front-runner, with a grand piano in one room and a commanding view 
of the Washington skyline. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roy Blunt came after me for months,'' said Rep. Jerry Weller  
of Illinois, one of the group that met with Bush that day. ``I 
said, how could I endorse someone for president if I've never had a 
conversation with him either in person or on the phone?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
