<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> School Wants Apology Over Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The head of an East Harlem school says Miramax  
Films should apologize for a new Meryl Streep film that depicts the 
school as plagued by violence and shoddy teaching. 
</P>
<P>
	``In retrospect, we probably should not have used the name of  
the school,'' Elizabeth Clark, senior vice president of Miramax, 
said in response to objections raised by some educators about 
``Music of the Heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The film, which opened Friday, stars Streep as Roberta Guaspari,  
who received widespread notice for teaching violin at the Central 
Park East 1 elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	Educators say the film misrepresents the school, citing scenes  
such as a drive-by shooting, a racially hostile parent and an 
incident involving a student with a knife. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're taking it very seriously,'' said Larry Speigel, the  
school's assistant director. ``There's a lot of dissension about 
what has happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	School director Jane Andreas, who said she has not seen the  
film, said others had told her the school and its ``vibrant and 
wonderful neighborhood are portrayed as very dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Before the initial credits, (Miramax) should make an apology  
saying, `This is a misrepresentation,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Music of the Heart'' tells how, after a school board  
threatened to cut off funding for Guaspari's program, concert 
violinists Isaac Stern, Itzhak Perlman and Arnold Steinhardt 
stepped in to help by performing with her students at a Carnegie 
Hall benefit. Her violin program is now partially supported by a 
foundation, Opus 118. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Clark of Miramax said the film's producers had not intended  
to create a false impression. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not really about the actual school,'' she said. ``The  
school is just the canvas. The story is about how she (Ms. 
Guaspari) saved the music program. ... There is no violence that 
occurs in the school. It's a fictionalized school, and the name 
shouldn't have been used.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The name was used because the film ``is the story of Roberta  
Guaspari's life, and that is the school that she taught at,'' Ms. 
Clark said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nuances about why the school is so different are not what  
the movie is about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Guaspari, who was a consultant on the film, no longer  
teaches at CPE1 and holds classes at another area school, Ms. 
Andreas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Repeated calls seeking comment from Ms. Guaspari were referred  
to Miramax, which did not make her available. In a Miramax 
statement, Ms. Guaspari said she was ``very proud'' of the film. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not unusual for filmmakers to take a true story and  
expand on it to include composite and invented characters and 
fictionalized events for dramatic purposes,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times previously had quoted Ms. Guaspari as saying  
almost every calamity that befalls pupils in the film was a 
fabrication. ``You need to know that the environment they portrayed 
is not like our school,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
