<DOCNO> APW19991030.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 11:53:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Curators Seek Rockwell Reinvention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Perhaps the most recognized American painter of  
the 20th century, Norman Rockwell has always been loved by the 
masses but dismissed as pedestrian by most in the art world. 
</P>
<P>
	Curators of a new touring exhibit, which features the largest  
collection of his paintings outside the Norman Rockwell Museum in 
Stockbridge, Mass., hope to make Rockwell as popular in the 
galleries of New York and Los Angeles as he is in middle America. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the people who dismiss him only know him through the  
magazine covers and have never seen his work in person,'' exhibit 
co-curator Anne Knutson said during a break from preparations at 
Atlanta's High Museum of Art, where the seven-city tour begins Nov. 
6. 
</P>
<P>
	``But hopefully they'll come so they can see for themselves that  
he was a classically trained artist and his painting technique was 
outstanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Saturday Evening Post covers Rockwell is famous for  
started out as full-size paintings and will hang in the exhibit 
entitled ``Pictures for the American People.'' A companion book 
also is available, featuring essays by several art critics and even 
one by his son Peter, a model for several of Rockwell's paintings. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell, who left the Post in the mid-1960s for Look Magazine,  
died in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit features all the whimsy, detail and Americana  
Rockwell is known for, along with several pieces painted in the 
1960s and showcasing the civil rights movement. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Ms. Knutson, Rockwell would finish his paintings on  
deadline and send them via courier -- sometimes still wet -- from his 
home in Massachusetts to Philadelphia, where they would be 
photographed and shrunk for the cover shots. In some places, the 
actual covers will hang next to the paintings to allow for closer 
scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors will find a safety pin protruding from ``Babysitter,  
Babysitter'' and pieces of gravel incorporated into the artist's 
account of a moon landing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the true Rockwell,'' Ms. Knutson said of the  
paintings. 
</P>
<P>
	However, art historian Ann-Sargent Wooster says the exhibit may  
not be enough to convince longtime Rockwell critics who downplay 
the importance of his work. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of artists and art critics got into the field to revolt  
against just what Rockwell was doing,'' said Wooster, a professor 
at the School of Visual Arts in New York. ``Heck, there's a 
darkness to Disney movies now that isn't even in Rockwell's work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already 30,000 tickets have been sold two weeks before the show,  
which will travel to Chicago, Washington, San Diego, Phoenix, 
Stockbridge, Mass., and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will certainly bring in some people who ordinarily don't  
go to museums,'' said co-curator Maureen Hart Hennessey of the 
Rockwell Museum. ``But not only are we trying to reach new 
audiences, but introduce the whole Rockwell to people who only know 
part of his work.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 09:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Trying To Shed 'Wooden' Tag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOVER, N.H. (AP) -- Call it the vice presidential pause, a  
campaign ailment afflicting only the No. 2 man trying to become No. 
1. The chief symptom is a nagging stiffness of style. Untreated, it 
can make a candidate wooden, unpersuasive, even boring. 
</P>
<P>
	The diagnosis is by Al Gore, who says he was suffering from it  
until he cured himself of taking momentary timeouts in campaign 
speeches to consider whether a position he was taking would 
conflict with White House policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that split second of internal vetting, it goes with that  
job, I'm done with that,'' Gore said, in an overtime 
question-and-answer session after his debate with Bill Bradley, a 
formidable rival for the Democratic presidential nomination. ``And 
it feels liberating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He may be done with the habit of pausing to check his answers  
against presidential policy but obviously he is not done with that 
job. The vice presidency carries constraints when the man holding 
it runs on his own; and this time, there is the added burden of 
voter weariness with President Clinton and scandal. But it also has 
advantages; no vice president who sought his party's nomination has 
been denied it since 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore is not breaking with the policies of the administration in  
which, the president says, he has been a partner, not just a 
deputy. His problem is to be independent of the past without being 
disloyal to his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Independence is fine, but only the vice president could have  
arranged to have three members of the Clinton Cabinet come to 
Hanover Wednesday night to praise his performance in his first 
debate with Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	So Gore looks for openings, as in his repeated comments about  
the pesky pause to check a campaign position against Clinton 
policy, the habit he said was one of the reasons for his image 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got that stiff-and-wooden rap in the House and  
Senate,'' Gore said earlier, in an interview with The Associated 
Press. ``It has been as vice president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He certainly did not pause before answering the first question  
he got in the debate, about scandals in government. ``I understand 
the disappointment and anger you feel toward President Clinton,'' 
he said, although the name had not been mentioned. ``I felt it 
myself.'' But he said that Americans want to focus on the future 
now, that Clinton is his friend and that during the Monica Lewinsky 
scandal, he had been working for continuity and stability. 
</P>
<P>
	It all fits the month-old remodeling effort to spruce up the  
candidate and the campaign against the Bradley challenge. Gore said 
it has led him back to the kind of open, and open-ended, campaign 
sessions he held when he first ran for Congress, in 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	He made the Dartmouth College debate into one, inviting  
questions before the television cameras went on, and at the end, 
asking anybody who still had unanswered questions to stay in the 
hall and he would answer them. About 100 did. Gore spent an hour 
and a half with them, perched on the front edge of the stage. It 
took on the flavor of a campus bull session. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore told them that while he would rather have been unopposed  
for the 2000 nomination, the stiff competition from Bradley has 
been good for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I began to change my way of campaigning ... to shed some of  
the approaches that I had adopted as vice president,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is backing Gore, but the vice president hedges about the  
role of the president the rest of the way. ``He'll help me in the 
future,'' Gore said in the AP interview. ``I don't know how. We 
haven't talked about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Gore and his campaigners have talked about, constantly,  
since Sept. 29, is the campaign makeover that shifted headquarters 
from Washington to Nashville, Tenn., set the vice president about 
demanding a weekly diet of debates with Bradley and began the new 
look. 
</P>
<P>
	New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, who supports Gore, welcomes  
the new strategy. ``I have been one of the people advocating that 
he needs to be himself -- he needs to get out of the role of vice 
president,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, that is his official role. His challenge is to get beyond  
it, to convince voters that he can offer change. For the vice 
president, it is a balancing act. Bradley does not have to prove 
that he would be a change. He is new. 
</P>
<P>
	Hence, the Gore campaign overhaul. ``He's much more Al Gore the  
person,'' Shaheen said. ``I think people saw the real Al Gore,'' 
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said after the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	That does leave the question of what took him so long.  
</P>
<P>
	After all, he has been though seven campaigns for Congress and  
vice president, and a brief, futile one for president in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	So this is not a new line of work.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and columnist  
for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
