<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tucson To Vote on Water Restriction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- It took 20 years and billions of dollars to  
bring Colorado River water across the desert to thirsty Tucson. It 
took only three years, a funny taste and some burst pipes for 
voters to say ``no, thank you,'' and permanently restrict its use. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucson residents go to the polls again Tuesday, this time to  
decide whether to direct water officials to dump the once-prized 
water into dry stream beds to replenish their groundwater, with 
natural filtration. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of the outcome, the 1995 ban on pumping it through  
their taps will remain in effect, even as the city keeps on paying 
for the project. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballot question is not an easy one in a desert city whose  
groundwater supply is dwindling at the same time rapid growth is 
steadily bringing in more thirsty people. 
</P>
<P>
	``Control of water is power here. There's a lot of people  
fighting over that power,'' said Rich Wiersma, executive vice 
president of the Citizens Alliance for Water Security, which 
supports the ballot measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucson is the largest city in the nation still entirely  
dependent on groundwater for its drinking supply. Groundwater also 
irrigates the golf courses and lush lawns replacing the natural 
desert terrain. 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades ago, a 336-mile canal called the Central Arizona  
Project was created to pump Arizona's share of the Colorado River's 
water to Phoenix, Tucson and other communities. 
</P>
<P>
	The $4.7 billion cost of that project is shared among local,  
state and federal governments. Tucson pays $7 million a year toward 
that cost, whether it uses all of its share of the water or not. 
</P>
<P>
	But when Tucson Water first tried to send Colorado River water  
to half its customers in 1992 -- roughly 240,000 people at the time 
-- the utility failed to treat the water to match existing supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the water is more corrosive because it has more  
dissolved salts and minerals -- and it scoured old iron pipes and 
pumped rust and smelly sediment out of people's faucets. In some 
cases, pipes burst. 
</P>
<P>
	The extra minerals also gave the water a stronger taste,  
required bathers to use more soap and built up quickly in 
appliances such as evaporative coolers that are used to air 
condition homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We made a very serious error in the treatment method,'' Tucson  
Water spokesman Mitch Basefsky said. ``Ever since we've been 
dealing with outrage and mistrust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Basefsky says it is very good water, and notes that about  
25 million people in California, Nevada and Phoenix use and drink 
it each day. 
</P>
<P>
	However, because of the problems, deliveries in Tucson were  
halted in 1994 and the following year voters approved a ballot 
measure that bans Tucson Water from delivering directly to 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	So, while the city is still paying its share of the project, it  
is drawing only about 18 percent of its allotted share of the 
water; most of it goes to recharge the city's aquifer and the rest 
is used for farm irrigation. What Tucson doesn't use goes through 
other communities' faucets. 
</P>
<P>
	Proponents of the ballot measure, Proposition 200, argue that by  
pouring Tucson's allotment into stream beds and washes, the 
funny-tasting water would seep into underground aquifers while 
being filtered naturally. Then, the city's wells could bring it 
back to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents say the plan is scientifically flawed and that any  
water that does trickle underground would end up far away from city 
wells. In essence, it would be throwing the water away. 
</P>
<P>
	Some residents have just about given up on Colorado River water.  
</P>
<P>
	``We had nothing but trouble -- odor, stuff coming out, it  
stopped up our cooler. It was a mess,'' said Bill Staggs. ``I 
wouldn't want to take a chance on it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, however, he and other residents may not have a  
choice. 
</P>
<P>
	City attorneys are already prepared to challenge Proposition  
200. They argue that the ballot measure violates the state 
Constitution and city charter by withholding elected officials' 
salaries for noncompliance, limiting when the measure could be 
repealed or amended, and requiring more than a simple majority of 
the City Council and mayor to raise water rates. 
</P>
<P>
	And, left as it is, Tucson's groundwater supply could be used up  
by the year 2020, said Barbara Tellman, a senior research 
specialist at the University of Arizona Water Resources Research 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got a finite supply of water,'' she said. ``As growth  
continues, we will run out. The question is how soon.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
