<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa, N.H. Caucuses Put at Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHNSTON, Iowa (AP) -- This year's fight over the presidential  
nomination calendar could lead to the end of the 
first-in-the-nation status of Iowa and New Hampshire, Iowa 
Democratic Chairman Rob Tully said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality is it's going to be tough for us in 2004 to retain  
this,'' Tully said. ``There's a lot of animosity around the 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While a fight occurs every four years over the lineup of  
primaries and caucuses, this year's battle saw a split between Iowa 
and New Hampshire that could doom both, Tully said at a television 
taping. 
</P>
<P>
	The two parties use different systems to set their political  
calendars. Democrats establish national party rules, which spell 
out the calendar. Republicans let each state sort through the 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	In past election cycles, Republicans and Democrats in Iowa and  
New Hampshire have worked together to fend off challenges from 
other states seeking the attention that comes during early 
campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, things went differently.  
</P>
<P>
	Iowa went through four different dates for its precinct  
caucuses, forced to move earlier in the process as other states 
moved up. The final move came when Iowa set its events for Jan. 24 
after New Hampshire surprised everyone by picking Feb. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite frankly, the maneuvering in New Hampshire that forced us  
to go to the 24th has added fuel to the fire,'' said Tully, a 
member of the Democratic National Committee's special panel that 
deals with the political calendar. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you from personal experience that there are people  
on that committee who are salivating to get rid of Iowa and New 
Hampshire,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 18:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Skaters Win at Sprints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVO, Utah (AP) -- China's Yang Yang sprinted past Canada's  
Annie Perrault on the second lap and went on to win Saturday's 
women's 500-meter race at the short-track speed skating World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrault, the Olympic gold medalist in 1998, took the lead  
quickly but couldn't hold off Yang. 
</P>
<P>
	Perrault won the 500 in a World Cup meet in Montreal last week  
only to be disqualified for stretching -- lifting a skate off the 
ice in an effort to edge an opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here I finished second,'' Perrault said. ``It was nice for me.  
It was a very clean race. I started in front, but she passed me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yang was clocked in 45.305 seconds, while Perrault came in at  
45.474. 
</P>
<P>
	Chikage Tanaka of Japan was third at 45.522 and Dandan Sun of  
China fourth in 45.755. 
</P>
<P>
	Jaijun Li of China won the men's 500-meter sprint at Provo's  
Peaks Ice Arena in 42.772. 
</P>
<P>
	The new arena will play host to some Olympic hockey games in  
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Dong-Sung Kim of Korea was second in 42.940, narrowly edging  
Apolo Ohno of the United States, who was clocked in 42.944, while 
Takehiro Kodera of Japan was fourth in 43.545. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges advanced Ohno, the 17-year-old world junior champion,  
into the final after he was fouled in a semifinal race. Takafumi 
Nishitani of Japan, the reigning Olympic champion, was charged with 
the infraction and disqualified. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Cup continues Sunday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
