<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 03:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: School Closing Overblown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A school closed for one day because of a threat  
of violence from a group of teens was never in danger, says a 
lawyer for two youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Shields, who represents a brother and sister who were  
questioned in the alleged threat, contends that Mayor Michael R. 
White overreacted in canceling classes Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``South High School is not Columbine,'' Shields said in  
reference to the nation's deadliest school shooting last April. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no weapons at school, no violent acts. We understand  
there may have been some talk from one child regarding some actions 
against other students, but that's it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shields also noted that no charges have been filed against his  
clients, a 14-year-old boy and his 15-year-old sister. 
</P>
<P>
	Police did arrest four other students and questioned seven other  
teens Friday in the alleged plot, which White said may have been 
motivated by racial bias. Seventy percent of South's 1,500-student 
population is black. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor declined to comment on a report that the attack  
planned for Friday was similar to the one by Eric Harris and Dylan 
Klebold at Columbine in Littleton, Colo. Armed with guns and bombs, 
the two teen-aged gunmen killed 12 students and a teacher before 
killing themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	At South, the 11 students -- all suspended for 10 days -- are  
white and planned to disrupt the school with ``violent acts,'' 
according to the mayor, who said only that the students felt 
alienated. 
</P>
<P>
	White said the students planned to get weapons from an area gang  
but are not gang members. Police found two guns at one student's 
home but would not say where. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the students questioned, Sarah Jedd, 15, said the four  
who were arrested, all boys, had maps of South High with shooting 
positions. She said her name was included on the maps, but she 
wanted no part of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so unfair that I got dragged into this,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	White would not elaborate on details of the alleged plot or  
confirm a report by The Plain Dealer that the students gave written 
statements to police that they planned to use guns and homemade 
explosives to kill teachers, administrators and fellow students. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said the massacre was planned for just before noon  
Friday, when students would open fire in the cafeteria and the 
principal's office. The students also planned a suicidal shootout 
with police in a school courtyard, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	White didn't disclose the names of those arrested but The Plain  
Dealer, citing juvenile court records, identified them today as 
Adam Gruber, 14, and 15-year-olds John Borowski, Benjamin Balducci 
and Andy Napier. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said Napier was the ringleader and that his  
parents have admitted him to MetroHealth Medical Center for a 
psychiatric evaluation. The other three are in juvenile detention. 
</P>
<P>
	Each is charged with two counts of inciting violence and one  
count each of false alarm, aggravated menacing-ethnic intimidation 
and inducing panic. If convicted, they could be incarcerated until 
they are 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Byrd-Bennett, head of the 77,000-student school  
district, says classes will resume at South High on Monday with 
heightened security. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Columbine, authorities around the country have charged  
students with planning or threatening to carry out similar acts. 
The National Safety Center estimated at least 3,000 copycat bomb 
threats were made in the weeks after Columbine -- about five times 
the usual number. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, for example, Monmouth Regional High School in Tinton  
Falls, N.J., was closed because someone scrawled on a bathroom 
wall: ``The Trench Coat Mafia is here. Everyone is going to die the 
29th'' -- a reference to the group Klebold and Harris were 
associated with. The school was searched and will reopen Monday, 
but police had not found the culprit. 
</P>
<P>
	In Snohomish, Wash., police said a freshman was in juvenile  
detention after allegedly threatening to blow up his high school. 
Authorities found three, 6-inch-long homemade pipe bombs at his 
home. After being tipped by other students, police arrested the boy 
without incident when he arrived at Snohomish High School on 
Friday. No bombs were found in the school. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
