<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wash. Race Crucial to Both Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- In a largely rural part of Washington  
state best known for its peas and lentils, political money is 
flowing and TVs are echoing with attack ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The race is for only one seat in the state Legislature -- the  
state's only legislative election this year -- but it's crucial to 
both parties. 
</P>
<P>
	If voters in the 9th District break their six-decade Republican  
trend and go Democrat, it will put the divided House in Democrat 
control. The Senate and the governor's office are already held by 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, it's a big deal,'' said Republican state Rep. Clyde  
Ballard, a co-speaker since the two parties must share power in the 
House, which is split 49-49. 
</P>
<P>
	Both parties have poured money into the race between incumbent  
state Rep. Don Cox, a 59-year-old educator and Republican, and 
Democrat Mike Connelly, a lawyer and school board chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox was appointed to the seat in January to succeed another  
lawmaker who was appointed to a state Senate seat. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th District has roughly 150,000 people in a region called  
the Palouse, where farms on rolling hills grow peas, lentils and 
wheat. It stretches from Cheney to Clarkston along the southern 
half of the Washington-Idaho border. 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't elected a Democrat since 1936.  
</P>
<P>
	Cox, a Washington State University faculty member and retired  
Colfax school superintendent, has raised $170,000 from a number of 
corporations, political action committees, individuals and the 
Republican Party, according to state records. 
</P>
<P>
	Connelly, 45, the son of U.S. Attorney Jim Connelly, has raised  
about $114,000 from labor organizations, other lawyers, individuals 
and state Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Each candidate also has benefitted from large cash infusions  
from independent expenditure campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like it,'' Cox said Wednesday. ``With the money comes  
a lot of tension. I just think it's unfortunate that we've gotten 
this much attention in a local, citizen-legislature type race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Connelly offers himself as an independent Democrat who would use  
his status as tiebreaker to work for better educational funding, 
health care reform and to benefit farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox's campaign commercials portray him as a defender of  
education who opposed Democratic sponsored tax increases and 
supports equitable funding for rural schools. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
