<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 08:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hatch Holds on to High Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- He trails George W. Bush by 63 percentage  
points in the latest poll and by nearly that many millions in 
campaign dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, vows to continue the presidential  
candidacy he called ``the longest of the long shots'' when he 
entered the race in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some don't want to give me a chance at all, but nobody who  
knows me feels that way,'' said Hatch, who noted -- proudly -- that 
he's moved from 11th place at the bottom of the pack of Republican 
presidential candidates into fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	While that is true, the gain was largely a product of attrition.  
</P>
<P>
	A field that began with 12 candidates now has six Republicans  
and Pat Buchanan, who left the GOP on Monday to seek the Reform 
Party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, former Vice President Dan Quayle, Lamar  
Alexander and Rep. John Kasich of Ohio have dropped out. New 
Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith became an independent before dropping out 
but recently has made overtures about returning to the GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said the chance that the front-running Bush might spend  
$100 million made it ``virtually impossible'' for him to win the 
nomination. Dole also cited the fund-raising disadvantage as a 
reason for quitting. The odds against Hatch are even longer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gallup poll found 66 percent of Republicans surveyed backing  
Bush, the Texas governor, and 3 percent of them supporting Hatch. 
The Oct. 21-24 survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Bush has raised more than $57 million to Hatch's $1.3  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most candidates are swimming away from their sinking ships,  
and Senator Hatch is still swimming toward his,'' said Alex 
Castellanos, a Republican media consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch has tried to sell himself as the GOP's ``Plan B'' should  
Bush falter. But Sen. John McCain of Arizona holds second place now 
that Dole is gone, although he trails Bush by 50 points or more, 
according to the latest national polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Bush falters it's not going to be Hatch; it's not going to  
be (Steve) Forbes. It's going to be McCain,'' said Rich Galen, a 
Washington-based GOP strategist. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch accuses Bush and McCain of abandoning their conservative  
roots to woo moderates. But he says he doesn't see Republicans 
flocking to McCain's bandwagon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not the way he has run down the Republicans,'' said Hatch,  
referring to McCain's strident criticism of senators who disagreed 
with his failed legislation to overhaul federal campaign finance 
laws. ``He's moving toward the moderate to liberal people in the 
party, and it's going to be a conservative electorate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Hatch said he would throw out the tax code,  
disband the Internal Revenue Service, rebuild the military, give 
local communities control over schools and appoint judges who he 
believes aren't activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are starting to catch on that I'm the only candidate  
with common-sense conservative ideas and the experience to be 
effective from day one,'' said the 23-year Senate veteran and 
Judiciary Committee chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch spokesman Jeff Flint said the campaign plans television  
ads leading into the Iowa caucuses next Jan. 24 and New Hampshire 
primary on Feb. 1. The push is funded in part by federal matching 
dollars the campaign expects to qualify for early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Matching funds don't indicate a viable candidacy, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Hatch expects to collect about $1 million in federal funds,  
leaving him well behind the rest of the field but adding life to a 
frugal campaign that so far has spent about $1 million -- almost as 
much as he has raised since the beginning of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	He seems convinced he will be in the race for the long haul.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a marathon, not a sprint,'' said Hatch, who admitted  
there may be a time to stop running but believes the campaign is 
working well now. 
</P>
<P>
	``If things keep going the way they are, you bet your life I  
will be around,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others aren't so convinced.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a pretty smart guy and at some point his family and staff  
are going to get together and say, 'Bush isn't going to collapse 
...,' and he's going to get out like the gentleman he is,'' said 
Galen, the Republican strategist. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 22:21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bradley Gaining on Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley is trailing Vice President Al  
Gore but has cut the margin, in the Democratic presidential race, 
says a poll released Saturday. The margin between Gore and Bradley 
has fluctuated in polls in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest Newsweek poll suggests Gore favored by 40 percent of  
registered Democrats or those who lean toward voting Democratic, 
while Bradley was the favorite of 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-percentage-point lead represents a drop from the vice  
president's 49-26 margin in the same poll a week ago. Bradley had 
cut the gap to 12 points in the CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll early 
this month, but Gore doubled his lead in that poll earlier this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newsweek poll also suggests Pat Buchanan's entry into the  
Reform Party could lure Republican voters away from GOP candidates, 
including top contender George W. Bush. The Texas governor, 
however, continues to hold a big lead, 63 percent to 12 percent for 
Arizona Sen. John McCain and 9 percent for publisher Steve Forbes 
in the race for the GOP nomination. Other candidates were in low 
single digits. 
</P>
<P>
	In a three-way race among Gore, Bush and Pat Buchanan, the poll  
found Bush favored by 46 percent of voters, Gore 39 percent and 
Buchanan 7 percent. In a Bush-Bradley-Buchanan race, Bush got the 
nod from 43 percent, Bradley 38 percent and Buchanan 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	When Buchanan is not in the mix, Bush was a 53 percent to 39  
percent choice over Gore. Bush was favored over Bradley, 49 percent 
to 41 percent, in a head-to-head matchup. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll was based on interviews with 630 registered voters last  
Thursday and Friday. It was conducted by Princeton Research 
Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 4  
percentage points, was conducted after the first televised debate 
between Gore and Bradley. But few registered voters were aware of 
the forum, pollsters found. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 12:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Approves Anti-Cult Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *By CHARLES HUTZLER    	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writer    	
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Calling Falun Gong an unprecedented threat to  
communist rule, China's legislature paved the way Saturday for 
leaders of the banned spiritual movement to be given lengthy prison 
terms and the death penalty at upcoming trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly unanimous passage of a new anti-cult law by the  
legislature's executive committee inside the Great Hall of the 
People came as defiant Falun Gong followers trickled into adjacent 
Tiananmen Square for a sixth day of peaceful, largely passive 
protests. 
</P>
<P>
	Embarrassed by the demonstrations and under orders to quash  
them, police widened their security net to capture thousands of 
Falun Gong followers who have slipped into Beijing from around the 
country. Uniformed police questioned people on streets, and 
plainclothes officers trained high-powered binoculars on the vast 
square. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 30 followers were taken away from the square. One woman  
cried, and she and several others separately pressed hands in a 
gesture of prayer after they were placed inside a police minibus. 
</P>
<P>
	China's Foreign Ministry telephoned several foreign news  
organizations, warning them not to contact Falun Gong members. 
Security agents followed foreign reporters. One agent carried a 
travel bag with a hidden camera. Operated by a handheld remote 
control, the camera's motorized film drive audibly whirred with 
every picture taken. 
</P>
<P>
	By tightening the law on cults, the communist government sped up  
the trials of principal members already in custody. But the need 
for new measures shows how threatened Chinese leaders feel by Falun 
Gong and how undaunted its followers remain more than three months 
into a ban on the widely popular group. 
</P>
<P>
	In passing the law 114-0 with two abstentions, senior  
legislators called Falun Gong ``unprecedented in the 50-year 
history of the People's Republic in terms of its size of 
organization, influence, number of illegal publications as well as 
the damages it brought to the society,'' the government's news 
agency, Xinhua, said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the vote, the Standing Committee of the National People's  
Congress ordered police and prosecutors on ``full alert of cult 
activities and smash them rigorously,'' Xinhua reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The law revises a section of the criminal code to make leaders  
of Falun Gong and other group's labeled cults liable for 
prosecution for murder, fraud, endangering national security and 
other crimes punishable by more than the 2- to 7-year prison terms 
allowed for most organizers under the current statute. 
</P>
<P>
	In a directive issued immediately after passage of the law,  
China's chief prosecutors agency and the Supreme People's Court 
identified as offenses key activities Falun Gong has been accused 
of: illegal assembly, resisting bans, organizing across provincial 
lines and causing deaths by preventing medical treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The latter charge would open the way for leading members to be  
tried for murder, a death-penalty offense. Falun Gong practitioners 
are not to take medicine. The government has blamed the group for 
1,400 deaths, many of them among people who refused to be treated 
for illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	An offshoot of traditional schools of slow-motion exercise that  
channel unseen forces of nature to the body, Falun Gong blends in 
ideas from Buddhism and Taoism. Its practice is believed to promote 
health and morality and has drawn anywhere from 2 million 
followers, the Communist Party figure, to tens of millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Already the government has accused 13 principal members for  
disseminating state secrets, and one, Xu Xinmu, could be tried in 
the coming week, human rights groups report. Over the next two 
months, up to 50 leaders could be put on trial with a few given the 
death penalty, a Communist Party source said. 
</P>
<P>
	For rank-and-file members, the law encourages local governments  
to show leniency and ``to educate those deceived while punishing a 
small number of cult leaders,'' Xinhua said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who recant their beliefs and withdraw from cults are not  
to be prosecuted, the prosecutors and Supreme People's Court 
directive said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days, police in northeastern Jilin province sentenced  
without trial 12 women followers, all school teachers, to labor 
camps, mostly for one-year terms, the Hong Kong-based Information 
Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China reported. 
They join more than 100 other followers in the province's labor 
camps. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
