<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Devils Crash An Opening-Night Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Once again, the New Jersey Devils played the role of spoilers.  
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in a month, the Devils ruined the opening of  
a new arena when they beat the Carolina Hurricanes 4-2 on Friday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys knew what was going to happen coming in,'' said  
Devils coach Robbie Ftorek, referring to the 30-minute opening 
ceremonies at the Hurricanes' Raleigh Entertainment and Sports 
Arena. ``They just went out and got themselves loosened up and went 
right to our game plan and did a heck of a job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the season, the Devils also beat Atlanta when the  
Thrashers opened their new Philips Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually the other team is pretty psyched up and it makes it  
tougher on us, but we did a pretty good job,'' defenseman Scott 
Stevens said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, it was Chicago 4, Detroit 2; Buffalo 3, Florida 2 in  
overtime; and Anaheim 5, Washington 2. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey scored three goals in a three-minute span early in  
the third period to break open the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolina goaltender Arturs Irbe was sharp for the first 40  
minutes as the Hurricanes led 1-0 heading to the final period. But 
Irbe let in a soft goal from the blue line by 26-year-old rookie 
Brian Rafalski 51 seconds into the period. Krzysztof Oliwa and Petr 
Sykora followed with scores shortly thereafter as the crowd of 
18,730 turned quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	A tip-in by Bates Battaglia with 11:22 left brought the crowd  
back into the game. But the Devils, the best road team in hockey a 
season ago with an NHL-record 28 wins, held on down the stretch and 
scored an empty-net goal by Randy McKay with four seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	``Archie looked unbeatable for 40 minutes and then all of the  
sudden they were able to beat him three times in a short span,'' 
Carolina captain Ron Francis said. ``Our guys had some great 
chances late, but we just didn't get the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
                      *Blackhawks 4, Red Wings 2    	
</P>
<P>
	Doug Gilmour scored his 400th career goal and Steve Passmore  
made 37 saves as the visiting Blackhawks beat Detroit, ending the 
Red Wings' five-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean McAmmond, Bryan McCabe and Bryan Muir also scored for the  
Blackhawks, who won their second straight after an 0-4-4 start. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Duchesne and Chris Chelios had Detroit's goals as the Red  
Wings (7-2-1) lost for the first time in eight games since a 3-2 
loss to Dallas in their second game of the season. 
</P>
<P>
                       *Sabres 3, Panthers 2, OT    	
</P>
<P>
	Geoff Sanderson scored with 5.5 seconds left in overtime to lead  
the Sabres over the visiting Panthers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanderson took a pass from Curtis Brown and fired the puck past  
Florida goaltender Trevor Kidd for his fourth career overtime goal 
and first for the Sabres. 
</P>
<P>
	Stu Barnes scored the tying goal with 18 seconds left in  
regulation, knocking in a loose puck during a scramble in front of 
the Florida net with the Buffalo goaltender pulled for an extra 
skater. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres lost their most prominent player when goaltender  
Dominik Hasek reaggravated a groin injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, it doesn't feel good,'' said Hasek, who watched the  
five-minute overtime from the bench before heading to the dressing 
room for treatment. ``I hope I'll feel better in a day or so, but 
right now it's pretty painful.'' 
</P>
<P>
                      *Mighty Ducks 5, Capitals 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Anaheim, Paul Kariya scored the first and last goals of the  
game as the Mighty Ducks beat the Capitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Between his first- and third-period goals, Kariya and his  
linemates continued to make life miserable for the Capitals, whom 
the Ducks routed 7-1 on Oct. 19 in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Kariya added two assists as he, right wing Teemu Selanne and  
center Matt Cullen combined for 10 points to torment Washington 
goalie Olaf Kolzig. Selanne scored his sixth goal of the season and 
added three assists, and Cullen had two assists. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time that Kariya and Selanne had four points  
apiece as teammates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
