<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Saturday, Oct. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Boeing Delay Dismays Safety Panel  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Federal officials say they have no evidence that  
Boeing Co. intentionally covered up a safety report that may have 
helped investigators determine what caused the TWA Flight 800 crash 
in 1996. But the NTSB said in a statement Friday it was unhappy 
about the three-year delay between the crash and the discovery of 
the report this spring. The report focuses on whether excess heat 
from air conditioners in Boeings E-4B military jet could create 
highly flammable fuel vapors in the central fuel tank. A Boeing 
spokesman said today that differences between the E-4B and the 747 
made the report largely irrelevant to the TWA investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Students Said Inspired by Columbine  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- A friend of the teens accused of plotting a  
deadly attack at their high school said they laughed about the 
Columbine massacre and wanted to replicate the rampage in 
Cleveland. Sarah Jedd, 15, said in Saturday's Plain Dealer that the 
students wanted to be ``well known.'' Four white students have been 
arrested and seven others questioned in what was described as a 
racially motivated plot to carry out an attack at predominantly 
black South High School. Mayor Michael R. White closed South High 
Friday after the parents of a student tipped off authorities. 

</P>
<P>
	China Approves Anti-Cult Law  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's legislature on Saturday passed a new  
anti-cult law that paves the way for leaders of the banned Falun 
Gong to be given lengthy prison terms and the death penalty at 
upcoming trials. By tightening the law on cults, the communist 
government sped up the trials of principal members already in 
custody. But the need for new measures shows how threatened Chinese 
leaders feel by Falun Gong and how undaunted its followers remain 
more than three months into a ban on the widely popular group. 

</P>
<P>
	Leader Criticizes Slave Labor Offer  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- A Jewish leader on Saturday criticized the amount  
German industry wants to pay former Nazi laborers as ``shameful,'' 
but a spokesman for the companies said they had no plans to raise 
their $3.2 billion offer. The public arguments cast further doubt 
that talks to settle on an amount, planned for next month in Bonn, 
would go forward. The German government and lawyers have both said 
they believe the meeting scheduled for Nov. 16-17 likely will be 
postponed. 

</P>
<P>
	Georgia Leader Vows Economy Reform  
</P>
<P>
	TBILISI, Georgia (AP) -- President Eduard Shevardnadze promised  
Saturday -- the day before Georgia's parliamentary election -- that 
the former Soviet republic would see a ``180-degree turn'' in its 
gloomy economic situation. His Union of Citizens of Georgia party 
was favored to win elections Sunday. Its closest rival is the 
Georgian Renaissance Union, headed by popular regional leader Aslan 
Abashidze. The campaign has been dominated by discussion of the 
economy. While Georgia's standard of living has improved since 
Shevardnadze took office in 1992, following a bloody rebellion that 
devastated the economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Daylight Savings Ends at 2 a.m.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Don't forget to ``fall back'' Sunday morning.  
Clocks shift back one hour at 2 a.m. Sunday, local time, giving an 
extra hour of sleep to most people tonight, but an extra hour of 
work to those on the overnight shift. The change also means it will 
be dark an hour earlier on Halloween, calling for extra caution on 
the part of drivers and those watching the children on their 
rounds. Daylight-saving time returns April 2. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Hire Baylor To Manage Team  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Don Baylor has been hired to manage the Chicago  
Cubs, taking over a last-place team that was plagued by injuries 
last season. Baylor, the hitting coach of the Atlanta Braves last 
season after six years as manager of the Colorado Rockies, had been 
courted by several major league teams, including the Anaheim Angels 
and Milwaukee Brewers. While there was no announcement by the Cubs, 
his hiring was confirmed to The Associated Press by a senior major 
league team official who spoke on the condition he not be 
identified. 

</P>
<P>
	No. 8 Nebraska 24, Kansas 17  
</P>
<P>
	LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Eric Crouch's 49-yard touchdown pass to  
Bobby Newcombe with 3:24 left lifted No. 8 Nebraska to a 24-17 
victory over Kansas on Saturday, giving the Cornhuskers their 31st 
consecutive victory over the Jayhawks. Crouch also ran for one 
score and Newcombe returned a punt 86 yards for another TD for 
Nebraska (7-1, 4-1 Big 12), which trailed 9-0 at halftime. Kansas 
dropped to 3-6 and 1-4. Correll Buckhalter ran for 116 yards on 22 
carries for Nebraska, which won despite a lost fumble at Kansas' 
1-yard line and two missed field goals by Josh Brown. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  



































  	   	
</P>
