<DOCNO> APW19991030.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 10:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees the Team of the Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Joe Torre talks about the ghosts that seem to live in every nook  
and cranny of Yankee Stadium, permanent reminders of the history 
and aura that hangs over the place. 
</P>
<P>
	While managing this team of the decade and franchise of the  
century to its 25th World Series championship, Torre reflected on 
what it means to wear the Yankee pinstripes. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first got this job, I felt a little strange putting on  
the Yankee uniform because of all the tradition that went with 
being a part of this organization,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He recalled in his first spring training as manager how Reggie  
Jackson, Goose Gossage and Ron Guidry showed up as instructors. 
</P>
<P>
	``All those people, it's special,'' Torre said. ``There's a lot  
of history, a lot of pride involved with being part of this 
organization. You feel an obligation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it's because Yankee Stadium seems more like a baseball  
museum than it does a ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Out beyond the left field fence is Monument Park, a tribute to  
the players who created the tradition. Before each game he pitches, 
Roger Clemens goes out there to touch Babe Ruth's monument. Catcher 
Jorge Posada does the same to the one honoring Thurman Munson. 
</P>
<P>
	The monuments and plaques for all the old Yankees are bridges  
from the past to the present, a roadmap through a legacy of winning 
that is unmatched in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees' World Series titles are a benchmark of excellence,  
16 more championships than any other baseball team, nine more than 
any NFL or NBA franchise. Only the 23 Stanley Cups won by Montreal 
hockey teams come close, but that total was achieved by two teams, 
the Canadiens and the Maroons. 
</P>
<P>
	All around the Stadium, there are reminders of this team's rich  
and glorious history; pictures of Lou Gehrig's farewell speech; of 
Babe Ruth and Mickey Mantle; of Yogi Berra and Joe DiMaggio. 
</P>
<P>
	The players wore No. 5 patches on their uniform sleeves this  
season to honor DiMaggio, who died in March, and black arm bands in 
memory of Catfish Hunter, who died in September. It was Joe D. who 
uttered the words that seem to sum up the franchise's history so 
well: ``I thank the good Lord for making me a Yankee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is a sentiment shared by many through the years because being  
a Yankee usually means winning. From the time Ruth arrived in New 
York in 1920 and revolutionized baseball with the long ball, the 
Yankees have been the yardstick against which other teams are 
measured. 
</P>
<P>
	The success has resulted in 36 American League championships in  
78 years -- almost one every other year. That is a remarkable ratio 
made even more impressive by two significant dry spells. The 
Yankees went without a pennant from 1964-76 and again from 1981-96. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruth's Yankees had Murderers' Row and earned the nickname the  
Bronx Bombers. They swept the Series in 1927 and 1928, and again in 
1932 when The Babe's called shot left a permanent imprint on the 
event. Like those teams, Torre's Yankees have won 12 straight World 
Series games. 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaggio's Yankees duplicated the back-to-back sweeps in  
1938-39. Torre's Yankees also achieved back-to-back sweeps. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1949, the Casey Stengel dynasty began, delivering 10 pennants  
in 12 years. There were two sets of five straight championships -- 
1949-1953 and 1960-64. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees established their dominance at a simpler time in  
baseball history. When they began beating up the baseball world, 
teams advanced directly from regular-season league championships to 
the World Series. Now, getting to the ultimate goal is more 
complicated because of the land mines in the divisional playoffs 
and League Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, the Yankees had to beat 15 other teams for the  
championship. Now they must beat 29. Still, they seem to find a 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	They are resilient and opportunistic, as different from the  
teams that preceded them as Muhammad Ali was from Joe Louis. They 
win with jabs instead of knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre said they are a perfect team for New York.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a special city,'' he said. ``There's a lot of energy.  
I think that's what the Yankees feed off, the energy of the city. I 
think it's a combination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their tradition goes beyond winning.  
</P>
<P>
	Some years ago, a rookie showed up in training camp and  
requested uniform No. 3. It was quietly explained to him that No. 3 
belonged to Ruth and no longer was available -- along with 14 other 
numbers the Yankees have retired to honor the heroes who wore them. 
</P>
<P>
	No team has taken more numbers out of circulation. That's  
because no team has had as many players it needed to honor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at all the pictures hanging here,'' Torre said. ``Ruth  
and Gehrig and DiMaggio, all the grace and elegance. There's a 
certain elegance about wearing a Yankee uniform and the way guys 
did it. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many uniforms have changed over the years and the Yankees  
have maintained their style and their class of the pinstripe, no 
names on the back, just the Yankees. You don't have to be in 
baseball or even be a sports fan to know who the New York Yankees 
are.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 12:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Fire Piersall From Minors Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Jimmy Piersall, known for outrageous behavior in  
a career in baseball that's spanned more than four decades, says he 
was fired as a Chicago Cubs minor league instructor because of 
critical remarks he made about the team's management. 
</P>
<P>
	Piersall was fired Friday for ``issues relating to his  
performance in player development,'' said Cubs general manager Ed 
Lynch. ``We've always viewed his public comments separately from 
that as employee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Piersall says he thinks he was fired because of a remark he  
made on a radio program after Jim Riggleman was fired as manager of 
the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Piersall said ``two other guys'' should have been fired instead  
of Riggleman -- leaving little doubt he was talking about Lynch and 
Cubs president Andy MacPhail. 
</P>
<P>
	Piersall, 69, was told of the Cubs' decision by Jim Hendry, the  
team's director of player development and scouting. Piersall told 
the Chicago Tribune he didn't ask the reason. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me put it this way,'' Piersall said, ``I've been doing it  
for 14 years with the Cubs and eight years on 'The Score,' (WSCR-AM 
1160) and no one said anything. Now I'm having problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piersall has long been one of the true characters of baseball.  
To celebrate his 100th home run, he circled the bases running 
backward. He once threw a baseball and an orange at the exploding 
scoreboard at Comiskey Park. His nervous breakdown in 1952 was the 
basis for the film, ``Fear Strikes Out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piersall also worked with the late Harry Caray as a broadcaster  
for the White Sox. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
