<DOCNO> APW19991030.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 12:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SLA History Allowed in Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The bombing conspiracy trial of an alleged  
former member of the Symbionese Liberation Army may become a forum 
for prosecutors to explore the history of the group in California, 
an undertaking which the defense said could last a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sara Jane Olson is to stand trial on 24-year-old charges she  
planted bombs under police cars for the radical group in 1975. The 
devices did not explode. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet while Ms. Olson has claimed she is being tried for all the  
SLA's crimes, the group's history may be relevant, Superior Court 
Judge James Ideman said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems we are going to have the whole history of the  
Symbionese Liberation Army in California put on in this 
courtroom,'' Ideman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge did not issue a ruling that the group's activities  
would be fair game at trial. Instead, he offered the observation 
during a pre-trial hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge said the prosecutors intend to try to show ``she  
should have known what she was getting involved in'' when she 
joined the group. 
</P>
<P>
	The group is best known for the February 1974 kidnapping of  
Patty Hearst, though earlier members of the group were convicted of 
killing Oakland schools chief Marcus Foster. There were also a 
series of bank robberies in Northern California. Ms. Olson is not 
charged with any of those crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Olson, formerly Kathleen Ann Soliah, was not associated with  
the SLA when the group abducted Hearst from her Berkeley apartment. 
Now known as Patty Hearst Shaw, she has been ordered to testify at 
Ms. Olson's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Susan Jordan said that including the group's  
history would drag the trial out a year, a claim prosecutors 
disputed. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Olson was indicted in 1976 and was a fugitive until June,  
when she was arrested in St. Paul, Minn., after being featured on 
TV's ``America's Most Wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was present for the proceeding but did not speak.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
