<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP President's Son Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A son of NAACP President Kweisi Mfume could  
face up to seven years in prison after pleading guilty to drug 
conspiracy and weapons charges and admitting he sold cocaine for 
more than two years in the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald T. Gray, 29, entered the plea Thursday in U.S. District  
Court here to a grand jury indictment charging him with three 
counts of distributing powdered cocaine and three charges of using 
the telephone to arrange drug sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray was arrested last May at his home by agents with the Drug  
Enforcement Administration. Assistant U.S. Attorney John Crabb Jr. 
said DEA agents recovered a 12-gauge shotgun and drug paraphernalia 
after arresting Gray. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Gray came to the attention of the DEA last  
spring after another area man was caught with drugs and said Gray 
had provided him with cocaine on at least 70 occasions, prosecutors 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray is one of five sons of Mfume, whose birth name was Frizzell  
Gray. Sentencing was scheduled for Feb. 11. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
