<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Time To Set Clocks Back One Hour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America falls back to standard time at 2 a.m.  
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	That means it's time to set the clock back one hour before  
retiring tonight, or risk being early for church or other 
activities Sunday except in all or part of three states. 
</P>
<P>
	It also means that dark will come an hour earlier on Sunday  
night -- Halloween when the little ones are out collecting goodies. 
Safety officials urge special care by drivers and parents because 
of that. 
</P>
<P>
	Daylight-saving time returns on April 2, 2000.  
</P>
<P>
	Arizona, Hawaii and the part of Indiana in the Eastern time zone  
remain on standard time throughout the year, so there'll be no 
movement of the clocks there. The same applies in the U.S. 
territories of Puerto Rico, the Virgin Islands and American Samoa. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 14:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fan Killed in Belgrade Soccer Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A teen-age soccer fan was killed  
Saturday when he was struck by a flare fired by a supporter of a 
rival team during a match between the country's two leading clubs, 
the Tanjug news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Red Star fans, angry at the flare believed to have been fired by  
someone on the Partizan side, smashed hundreds of seats in the 
stands before police restored order. At least 146 people were 
arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	The match continued, however, before some 30,000 fans. Partizan  
won 2-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the country's Soccer Association was expected to  
take undisclosed measures against the club whose fans caused the 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The game was held at Partizan's stadium. The club issued a  
statement expressing regret and saying the incidents happened 
despite ``utmost security precautions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
