<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forbes Attacks Bush Over Substance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Steve  
Forbes continued his assault Saturday on GOP front-runner George W. 
Bush, saying the Texas governor's campaign amounted to little more 
than ``a backslap and a slogan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes and presidential rival Gary Bauer, courting voters in  
South Carolina's conservative Upstate region, tried to position 
themselves as the alternative to a moderate Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina's Feb. 19 primary is considered an early  
barometer of how candidates will do in the conservative South. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates spoke at a GOP convention in Greenville County,  
an area of South Carolina politically dominated by the Christian 
right. Arizona Sen. John McCain, whose wife, Cindy, spoke at the 
Greenville event, was scheduled to appear later Saturday at a 
reception in the lower part of the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said he wants to be the issue-driven candidate rivaling  
Bush's lack of substance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The voters are starting to notice,'' he said, referring to  
Bush's drop in New Hampshire polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes has gone after Bush for skipping two New Hampshire  
debates, including one last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush had a representative, Rep. Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas,  
speak to the convention on his behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes said he won't have to launch a series of attack ads at  
Bush. Instead, he'll put forth ads showcasing his issues and ideas, 
much like he did in 1996 against GOP front-runner Bob Dole. That 
should be damaging enough to Bush, whose ``compassionate 
conservatism'' message remains a mystery to voters, Forbes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What does this slogan mean,'' he said. ``As they used to say,  
where's the beef? And it comes from Texas. Where's the beef? What 
is he talking about?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican House Speaker David Wilkins of Greenville, a Bush  
supporter, laughed off the candidates' attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not speaking for the governor, but I doubt seriously he'd  
trade places with them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes and Bauer also struck at Bush on the abortion issue. Both  
said that opposition to abortion would be a requirement for any 
court appointment they would make as president. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has said he's ``strongly pro-life'' but also thinks the  
nation isn't ready for a constitutional amendment banning abortion. 
He says he would refuse to apply litmus tests in appointing only 
judges who oppose abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer's criticism wasn't only for Bush. He blasted Forbes, the  
millionaire publisher who is financing his own campaign, for a flat 
tax plan that Bauer said would free big companies of taxes and 
burden working class Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``His proposal would destroy the Republican party,'' Bauer said,  
urging Republicans to return to the era of Ronald Reagan and 
embrace the ``little guy,'' not just corporate America. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
