<HEADLINE> Air Force DB Knocked Unconscious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVO, Utah (AP) -- Air Force defensive back Tony Metters was  
knocked unconscious and was removed by ambulance during the fourth 
quarter of BYU's 27-20 victory over Air Force on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Metters, a 6-foot, 185-pound junior safety from Mansfield,  
Texas, was injured on a 57-yard scoring pass from Kevin Feterik to 
Margin Hooks with 10:18 remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Metters and Wes Glisson converged on Hooks as the ball arrived,  
and the collision put both Air Force players on the ground. Hooks 
kept his balance and outraced three other defenders to the end 
zone. 
</P>
<P>
	After the play, Metters lay on the turf 12 minutes as trainers  
from both teams attended. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force officials said Metters had a bloody nose but, after  
regaining consciousness, was able to move his arms and legs. He was 
taken to Utah Valley Regional Medical Center for a precautionary 
neurological examination. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials later said tests showed no brain damage and Metters  
returned to the Air Force Academy in Colorado with the team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
