<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Akamai Shares Soar in IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares in Internet technology company Akamai  
Technologies Inc. surged more than 450 percent in initial trading, 
the fourth-best IPO ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cambridge, Mass.-based Akamai closed Friday at $145.18 3/4 on  
the Nasdaq Stock Market after it was initially priced at $26 a 
share and opened at $110. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock's 458 percent increase from its initial price ranks it  
fourth, behind theglobe.com (606 percent), Foundry Networks (525 
percent) and Marketwatch.com (474 percent), financial market 
researcher Securities Data Corp. said. 
</P>
<P>
	Akamai sold 9 million shares to raise more than $1.3 billion.  
Its closing share price gave it a stunning market value of more 
than $13 billion -- even though Akamai had sales of just $1.3 
million and lost $28.3 million in the first nine months of this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Akamai (pronounced AH-kuh-my) is Hawaiian for intelligent,  
clever and cool. 
</P>
<P>
	Formed last year, it offers Yahoo! and other Web destinations a  
service that delivers the most image-intensive portions of their 
Web pages -- such as advertisements with colorful moving images -- 
through a speedier route than the public Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The service answers a common complaint that graphic-intensive  
Web pages take too long to download and can cause computers to 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for the Akamai service is ``immense,'' said Ullas Naik,  
an analyst with FAC EquitiesFirst Albany, a Boston-based investment 
firm. ``It's going to keep growing significantly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To provide the service, Akamai owns a global network of 1,475  
computer servers and rents space on them to Web companies such as 
Yahoo! These Web destinations use the servers to store graphic-rich 
information closer to Internet users' computers, circumventing part 
of the crowded public information highway. 
</P>
<P>
	The Akamai technology is based on the initial work of F. Thomas  
Leighton, a math professor at the Massachusetts Institute of 
Technology, and one of his students, Danny Lewin. 
</P>
<P>
	Leighton is Amakai's chief scientist. The company's chief  
executive, George H. Conrades, was a senior vice president of 
International Business Machines Corp. and president of Internet 
pioneer BBN Corp., which he sold to GTE Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies with investments in Akamai include Apple Computer  
Inc., network equipment supplier Cisco Systems Inc. and Microsoft 
Corp. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 14:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
