<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reburial in Flooded N.C. Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Federal teams have begun reburying  
coffins unearthed by Hurricane Floyd's unforgiving floodwaters, as 
relatives of the dead endure the pain of saying goodbye once again. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I read about all the caskets coming out of the ground, I  
said 'Not mine,''' said John Ricks, of Dale City, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the coffins of his wife Elizabeth, and 9-year-old son  
David, killed in a traffic accident 21 years ago, floated to the 
surface when 20 inches of rain brought the Tar River to record 
levels, flooding Tarboro and Princeville and swallowing local 
cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricks bit his lip and wiped his eyes on Friday as he waited with  
other relatives for the caskets to be reburied. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a relief, and at the same time, it's like stirring stuff  
up again, because I never stopped loving them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family's caskets were among 224 that floated away during the  
flooding. Boat crews corralled the caskets and tethered them to 
trees or anything else solid while the water remained high, then 
recovered them after it receded. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 200 state and federal employees joined volunteers in  
working to identify the remains in a warehouse used as an emergency 
morgue. Inside, gray caskets sat row upon row, most marked with 
``PV'' and a number, denoting their final destination as 
Princeville. Others bore markings for relocation to six other 
counties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have dealt with floods numerous times in this state, but  
this is the first time we have dealt with anything of this nature, 
certainly on this scale,'' said Elaine Wathen, area coordinator for 
the state Emergency Management Division. 
</P>
<P>
	Specialists with the U.S. Public Health Service's Disaster  
Mortuary Operational Response Team used body markings, jewelry and 
pacemaker serial numbers in trying to identify the corpses. Wall 
charts listed amputated limbs, yellow hair and other features on 
unclaimed bodies -- something families never see. 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst part of it is when you bury your family, you think  
that's their final resting place and then this happens,'' said Dean 
Snow of Richmond, Mo., a member of the mortuary team. ``It's pretty 
rough on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of those recovered, 175 caskets have been identified, officials  
say. About 20 are to be reburied each day. 
</P>
<P>
	Each casket gets a new headstone paid for by the government and  
is buried under 18 inches of earth. A red rose, purchased with the 
team members' personal funds, is placed on each fresh grave. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Ricks' reburial, the coffins of Elizabeth and David were  
gently brought into newly dug graves beside his two other children 
who also died in the wreck, and then a backhoe covered the graves 
with sandy soil. The family read the 23rd Psalm and sang ``Amazing 
Grace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It means everything to me,'' said Dorothy Whitehead, mother of  
Elizabeth. ``I'm so glad the government thought enough of these 
flooded people to put them back in a casket and rebury them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991030.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-30 07:00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eight-Year IOC Terms Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- IOC members will face re-election  
after eight-year terms of office but current delegates will still 
be eligible to continue until the age of 80, under recommendations 
made today by an Olympic reform panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The issues of age limits and term limits dominated the debate at  
the morning session of IOC 2000, an 80-member task force set up by 
the International Olympic Committee in the wake of the Salt Lake 
City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel was examining 50 proposals drafted by its executive  
committee. The final recommendations will be submitted to the full 
IOC general assembly at a special session in Lausanne on Dec. 
11-12. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission endorsed a proposal for an age limit of 70, but  
the rule will apply only to future members. The existing 100-plus 
delegates would continue to be covered by the 80 age limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as current members are concerned, the executive  
committee believes that their rights should be preserved,'' the 
document said. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said the only change in the  
status of current members would be the introduction of a renewable 
eight-year term of office. Members would come up for re-election in 
2008. 
</P>
<P>
	``The actual members in place today can reach the limit of 80  
but will be re-elected every eight years,'' IOC executive board 
member Jacques Rogge said. ``It's a compromise. It's the price to 
pay to have a two-thirds majority (at the December session).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The age limit was raised in 1995 from 75 to 80 in order to allow  
Samaranch to seek another term. If the 70 limit were applied to 
today's members, 24 would have to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we take the rights away of more than one-third of IOC  
members, we have no chance for the reforms to get through,'' said 
executive board member Marc Hodler. 
</P>
<P>
	The longest debate centered on the recommendation for future IOC  
presidents to be limited to one eight-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	Many delegates objected, saying presidents should have a chance  
to run for a second term of four or eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Greek IOC member Lambis Nikolaou pointed out that there have  
been only seven presidents in the IOC's 105-year history. 
Samaranch, due to step down in 2001, has been in office since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is the stability of the IOC,'' Nikolaou said. ``The IOC  
has survived two world wars and now it seems like we want to pass 
with a bulldozer over the IOC. If you have a capable president, why 
should you have to tell him to leave after eight years?'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice presidents Keba Mbaye and Kevan Gosper argued in favor  
of the single term. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's world, eight years is a very reasonable time to  
give enormously to an organization,'' Gosper said. ``Even the 
United States restricts its president to eight years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With no consensus reached, Samaranch said the issue would be  
left to the session in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Another divisive issue, whether to ban member visits from  
Olympic bid cities, was to be debated later Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive committee has recommended against visits,  
continuing a ban that was put into affect during bidding for the 
2006 Winter Games. But there is a strong feeling among many members 
that visits should be reinstated under tight controls. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch is opposed to site visits -- which were at the heart of  
the scandal over gifts and other inducements offered to members 
during Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Among recommendations approved Saturday:  
</P>
<P>
	-- the IOC to have a maximum of 115 members.  
</P>
<P>
	-- 15 active athletes to be appointed as full IOC members.  
</P>
<P>
	-- the renovated IOC to include 15 presidents of international  
federations and 15 presidents of national Olympic committees or 
continental associations. 
</P>
<P>
	-- 70 members to be elected on an individual basis.  
</P>
<P>
	-- creation of a special selection committee to screen candidates  
for IOC membership. 
</P>
<P>
	-- the executive board to be expanded from 11 member to 15, with  
a permanent seat reserved for athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekend meetings come at a time of increased scrutiny of the  
IOC by critics in the U.S. Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	At a congressional hearing earlier this month, lawmakers  
expressed skepticism about the reform efforts and threatened 
retribution if the organization fails to enact meaningful change in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
	Possible sanctions include legislation to cut off American  
corporate support for the Olympics and strip the IOC's tax-exempt 
status in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has agreed to testify in Congress about the reforms on  
Dec. 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
