<HEADLINE> Calif. Gun Show Draws Thousands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POMONA, Calif. (AP) -- The Great Western gun show, one of the  
largest in the country, drew thousands of patrons on Saturday after 
fighting off efforts by the county to shut it down. 
</P>
<P>
	The 22-year-old show, which runs through Sunday at the Los  
Angeles County fairgrounds, has become a focus of California gun 
control advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	County supervisors banned sales of weapons and ammunition on  
county property a month after five people were wounded in a 
shooting rampage at a San Fernando Valley Jewish community center 
and a Filipino-American postman was shot to death. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a federal judge issued a temporary injunction about two  
weeks ago that blocked the ordinance, allowing the show to proceed. 
</P>
<P>
	Aisles were jammed shoulder-to-shoulder with people admiring  
swords, Western revolvers, $900 assault-style rifles in camouflage 
colors, heaps of uniforms, piles of ammunition and curios ranging 
from old political campaign buttons to wooden dolphin carvings. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the 5,300 tables were filled with arsenals of guns,  
ranging from Chinese-made Kalashnikov knockoffs -- semiautomatic 
only -- to hunting rifles with gleaming wooden stocks and fancy 
inlays. 
</P>
<P>
	No problems or arrests were reported.  
</P>
<P>
	Harrison Carter, 13, came to the show with his father to find a  
target shooting and hunting rifle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been looking at a lot of M-16 clones, trying to find  
something with a good deal on them. A lot of them are in, like, the 
$1,000 range, though,'' Harrison said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
