<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Wants Fee Added to Phone Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators opened an investigation  
Friday into a request by AT&AMP;T Corp. to sharply increase fees that 
residential customers pay to subsidize phone service for the poor, 
people in expensive-to-serve areas and school Internet hookups. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest long-distance company, filed a  
request Friday with the Federal Communications Commission seeking 
to increase the fee by almost 52 percent, from 99 cents a month to 
$1.50. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC said late Friday that it would not let the proposed fees  
go into effect for now and opened an investigation to determine 
whether they are justified. If the FCC didn't act, the fees would 
have gone into effect. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission ``stopped these charges pending the outcome of an  
investigation to determine the reasonableness of AT&AMP;T's increase,'' 
the agency said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T justified the proposed fee increase as fair and necessary  
to cover its increased costs in providing the subsidized services. 
The subsidy requirements are imposed by the government on 
long-distance and other companies, which pass them along to 
customers in various charges on their phone bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a complex matter and we will go over our numbers and  
justification with the FCC as soon as possible,'' a AT&AMP;T 
spokesperson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC will give AT&AMP;T and all other interested parties an  
opportunity to weigh in on the matter before making a final 
decision. The commission is required to complete its investigation 
within five months, agency officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups assailed AT&AMP;T's request.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is an outrageous proposal,'' said Gene Kimmelman of the  
Consumers Union. ``It amounts to nothing more than price gouging to 
consumers, especially people who make few long-distance calls.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
