<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Seeks Catholic School Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Cheered on by thousands of children and  
teachers, Pope John Paul II on Saturday called for equal funding 
for Catholic schools in one of the biggest rallies at St. Peter's 
Square in years. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates ranged as high as 200,000 for the lively crowd, which  
filled the piazza and spilled out onto the long boulevard leading 
into the Vatican. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy's bishops and John Paul have pressed for government  
financial help for Catholic schools through tax credits to parents 
or other means. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent moves in that direction ``unfortunately were not  
enough,'' John Paul said. 
</P>
<P>
	The turnout from across Italy far surpassed the prediction of  
80,000. Politicians attended as well, with Italy's education 
minister among those applauding when John Paul urged parity between 
state and church schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling the current setup ``ever less bearable,'' John Paul said  
the solution was ``full recognition of legal and economic parity 
between state and non-state schools, overcoming the old objections, 
which are foreign to the basic values of the European cultural 
tradition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of state support for church schools has divided  
Italy's center-left government. Leftist opponents to the funding 
sent schoolchildren marching through Rome in their own, much 
smaller demonstrations earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The children's rally -- on a sunny autumn morning -- drew a rare,  
wide smile from the pope, whose face as he has aged has stiffened, 
which some attribute to Parkinson's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	A little boy and girl approached the papal throne to present  
bouquets of flowers, then milled about, as if unwilling to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul laughed out loud, leaning forward to stroke the  
children's faces. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
