<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Curators Seek Rockwell Reinvention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Perhaps the most recognized American painter of  
the 20th century, Norman Rockwell has always been loved by the 
masses but dismissed as pedestrian by most in the art world. 
</P>
<P>
	Curators of a new touring exhibit, which features the largest  
collection of his paintings outside the Norman Rockwell Museum in 
Stockbridge, Mass., hope to make Rockwell as popular in the 
galleries of New York and Los Angeles as he is in middle America. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the people who dismiss him only know him through the  
magazine covers and have never seen his work in person,'' exhibit 
co-curator Anne Knutson said during a break from preparations at 
Atlanta's High Museum of Art, where the seven-city tour begins Nov. 
6. 
</P>
<P>
	``But hopefully they'll come so they can see for themselves that  
he was a classically trained artist and his painting technique was 
outstanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Saturday Evening Post covers Rockwell is famous for  
started out as full-size paintings and will hang in the exhibit 
entitled ``Pictures for the American People.'' A companion book 
also is available, featuring essays by several art critics and even 
one by his son Peter, a model for several of Rockwell's paintings. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell, who left the Post in the mid-1960s for Look Magazine,  
died in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit features all the whimsy, detail and Americana  
Rockwell is known for, along with several pieces painted in the 
1960s and showcasing the civil rights movement. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Ms. Knutson, Rockwell would finish his paintings on  
deadline and send them via courier -- sometimes still wet -- from his 
home in Massachusetts to Philadelphia, where they would be 
photographed and shrunk for the cover shots. In some places, the 
actual covers will hang next to the paintings to allow for closer 
scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors will find a safety pin protruding from ``Babysitter,  
Babysitter'' and pieces of gravel incorporated into the artist's 
account of a moon landing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the true Rockwell,'' Ms. Knutson said of the  
paintings. 
</P>
<P>
	However, art historian Ann-Sargent Wooster says the exhibit may  
not be enough to convince longtime Rockwell critics who downplay 
the importance of his work. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of artists and art critics got into the field to revolt  
against just what Rockwell was doing,'' said Wooster, a professor 
at the School of Visual Arts in New York. ``Heck, there's a 
darkness to Disney movies now that isn't even in Rockwell's work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already 30,000 tickets have been sold two weeks before the show,  
which will travel to Chicago, Washington, San Diego, Phoenix, 
Stockbridge, Mass., and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will certainly bring in some people who ordinarily don't  
go to museums,'' said co-curator Maureen Hart Hennessey of the 
Rockwell Museum. ``But not only are we trying to reach new 
audiences, but introduce the whole Rockwell to people who only know 
part of his work.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
