<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Group Protests Zimbabwe Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Police arrested four gay rights campaigners  
Saturday after they attempted to make a citizen's arrest of 
Zimbabwe's President Robert Mugabe. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Tatchell, leader of a group called Outrage!, was arrested  
outside the Crowne Plaza hotel, according to one of the protesters. 
The group said they wanted to arrest Mugabe because of the alleged 
torture of two journalists in his country. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters had carried placards including one which said  
``Mugabe stop abusing queers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scotland Yard confirmed that four men had been arrested for  
criminal damage and public order offenses after they had jumped on 
to a car, but no names were released. Police would not say whether 
Mugabe was in the car, and no one answered the telephone at 
Zimbabwe's embassy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Foreign Office confirmed that Mugabe had arrived in London  
earlier this week for a brief visit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robert Mugabe has had a couple of days here on a private  
shopping trip and is going back to Zimbabwe this evening,'' said 
protester John Hunt, 47. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United Nations convention on torture has effect in this  
country, and we were intending to perform a citizen's arrest, and 
notified the attorney general,'' Hunt said. ``However, the police 
appeared to have misinterpreted their duty and have allowed Robert 
Mugabe to escape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two journalists in Zimbabwe were arrested earlier this year for  
their reporting on that nation's involvement in Congo's civil war. 
The men later appeared in court with serious injuries they said 
were inflicted during questioning by military officers. 
</P>
<P>
	The human right group Amnesty International has condemned the  
government for what it called the torture of the journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Mugabe has also been an outspoken critic of homosexuality.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
