<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Baylor Accepts Cubs Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Braves hitting coach Don Baylor has  
accepted an offer to manage the Chicago Cubs, according to The 
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs plan to announce Sunday that Baylor has agreed to a  
four-year deal worth an average of $1.3 million a season, the 
newspaper said in Sunday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to Cubs general manager Ed Lynch and the team's public  
relations staff by The Associated Press on Saturday night were not 
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor is returning to the managing ranks after one season as  
Atlanta's hitting coach after being fired by the Colorado Rockies 
following six years at the helm of an expansion team he led to the 
playoffs in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He also considered offers from Anaheim and Milwaukee.  
</P>
<P>
	``The stability of the Cubs and Wrigley Field won me over,''  
Baylor said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great move for me to make,'' he told the newspaper.  
``I've been in the league now for six years as a manager and as a 
coach. I know the league now. In the American League, I don't know 
as much, watching the slugfests over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor played his entire 19-year major league career in the AL.  
He spent six years with the Angels, winning the MVP award in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs fired Jim Riggleman after finishing last in the NL  
Central with the third-worst record in baseball (67-95), ahead of 
only the Florida Marlins (64-98) and Minnesota Twins (63-97). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
