<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College Football Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                              *STARS   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Ron Dayne rushed for 162 yards and two touchdowns as No. 11  
Wisconsin defeated Northwestern 35-19. He needs 321 in his last two 
games to break the NCAA career rushing record of 6,279 set last 
year by Texas' Ricky Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Spencer Romine passed for a career-high 404 yards and three  
touchdowns, including the game-winner to Scottie Montgomery with 
1:42 left, in Duke's 25-22 upset over Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	-- David Neill passed for 405 yards and four touchdowns and ran  
for a score as Nevada defeated North Texas 41-28. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Tim Rattay was 44-of-66 for 508 yards and three touchdowns as  
Louisiana Tech beat Toledo 34-17. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Chad Pennington was 26-of-33 for 288 yards, giving him 10,236  
yards in 2 1/2 seasons. He's four shy of becoming the third 
major-college quarterback to throw 100 TD passes. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Tony Taylor ran for 218 yards and three touchdowns in  
Northwestern State's 36-21 victory over Southwest Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Devin Scott was 36-of-45 for 311 yards and six touchdowns in  
Temple's 56-28 victory over Rutgers. Scott broke the school records 
of five TD passes and 32 completions. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Marques Tuiasosopo racked up a school-record 509 yards as  
Washington rallied to beat Stanford 35-30. Tuiasosopo completed 
19-of-32 passes for 302 yards and a touchdown and ran 22 times for 
207 yards and two TDs. He's the fourth major-college player to pass 
for 200 and rush for 200 in a game. 

</P>
<P>
                          *SWEATING IT OUT   	
</P>
<P>
	Hayden Epstein kicked a 20-yard field goal with 18 seconds to  
play as No. 15 Michigan defeated Indiana 34-31. Michigan had to bat 
down a pass in the end zone on the game's final play to avoid 
losing a third consecutive regular-season game for the first time 
since 1967. 

</P>
<P>
                          *STUNNING ENDING   	
</P>
<P>
	Kris Stockton kicked an 18-yard field goal as time expired to  
give No. 12 Texas a 44-41 victory over Iowa State. Starting at the 
Texas 28, Major Applewhite drove the Longhorns down the field in 
the final 3:20, setting up Stockton's game-winner. 

</P>
<P>
                        *SPURRIER MILESTONE   	
</P>
<P>
	Steve Spurrier earned his 100th victory at Florida as the  
fifth-ranked Gators defeated No. 10 Georgia 30-10. Doug Johnson was 
17-for-32 for 234 yards and Darrell Jackson caught six passes for 
141 yards in the Florida win. 

</P>
<P>
                             *STREAKS   	
</P>
<P>
	Jarious Jackson hit Jay Johnson for a 16-yard touchdown with 36  
seconds left and Notre Dame extended its NCAA-record winning streak 
over Navy to 36 games with a 28-24 victory. 

</P>
<P>
                            *SHELLACKED   	
</P>
<P>
	No. 6 Kansas State allowed just seven first downs and 119 yards,  
17 passing, while gaining 402 yards and 24 first downs in a 48-7 
victory over Baylor. 

</P>
<P>
                             *SHOOTOUT   	
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati defeated Miami of Ohio 52-42, marking the  
highest-scoring of the 104 games between the schools. Cincinnati 
rolled up 528 yards, Miami 408. 

</P>
<P>
                          *SIX HUNDRED WINS   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Casey Donaldson scored two touchdowns as Wittenberg became the  
first school below Division I to win 600 games by defeating Ohio 
Wesleyan 14-0. Wittenberg, a Division III school, is 600-318-32. 
</P>
<P>
	-- No. 22 Texas A&AMP;M beat Oklahoma State 21-3, winning its 600th  
game in school history. The Aggies are the 17th Division I-A school 
to reach that mark. 

</P>
<P>
                          *SETTING THE MARK   	
</P>
<P>
	Chris Redman became the career leader in completions in Division  
I-A, going 23-of-34 for 224 yards and two touchdowns in 
Louisville's 23-14 victory over UAB. Redman, who also holds the 
career attempts mark with 1,587, has 975 completions, 17 more than 
BYU's Ty Detmer. 

</P>
<P>
                            *SURPRISES   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Justin Hill threw two touchdown passes to Des Kitchings and  
ran for a score as Furman beat North Carolina 28-3. The Paladins 
got their first victory over a I-A opponent since 1985. The Tar 
Heels lost their sixth straight and their first ever to a I-AA 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Mike Moschetti passed for four touchdowns and ran for one, and  
the Colorado defense had four interceptions as the Buffaloes 
upended No. 24 Oklahoma 38-24. 

</P>
<P>
                         *SECOND HALF SURGE   	
</P>
<P>
	Kenny Kelly was 21-of-34 passes for 268 yards and two  
second-half touchdowns as No. 23 Miami beat West Virginia 28-20. 
The Hurricanes trailed 13-0 at halftime, the first time they had 
been scoreless at home at halftime in 15 years. Miami got its 
second come-from-behind victory in as many weeks, overcoming a 
28-point deficit to beat Boston College 31-28 last week. 

</P>
<P>
                          *SCHOOL RECORDS   	
</P>
<P>
	-- Defensive end Courtney Brown had four sacks, tying a Penn  
State record, and his 32 career sacks broke Larry Kubin's school 
record of 30. No. 2 Penn State defeated Illinois 27-7. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton passed for 212 yards and three  
touchdowns, giving him 53 on his career, breaking the school record 
of 51. The No. 7 Yellow Jackets defeated North Carolina State 
48-21. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Antwaan Randle El had 290 yards passing and threw four TDs in  
a 35-31 loss to No. 15 Michigan. Randle El now has 16 TD passes on 
the season, setting an Indiana record. 

</P>
<P>
                             *SPEAKING   	
</P>
<P>
	``You could call it a devastating loss. It breaks our heart. A  
36-year streak; we came 1 centimeter from ending it. It was that 
close,'' -- Navy safety Chris Lepore after a 28-24 loss to Notre 
Dame. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``I said all week I thought they were the best team in the  
history of the MAC. They are like a bomb. You know sooner or later 
they are going to go off, and you just hold your breath.'' -- 
Northern Illinois coach Joe Novak after a 41-9 loss to No. 13 
Marshall. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
